    371 </a><a href="#h4-0-148" id="h4-0-148" class="i">+          &lt;h2&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
    372 </a><a href="#h4-0-149" id="h4-0-149" class="i">+          &lt;p&gt;
    373 </a><a href="#h4-0-150" id="h4-0-150" class="i">+            My name is Hctor Aldair Aguilar. I&#39;m a front-end developer who
    374 </a><a href="#h4-0-151" id="h4-0-151" class="i">+            enjoys making websites. I love the web with all its weirdness. This
    375 </a><a href="#h4-0-152" id="h4-0-152" class="i">+            is just my little personal place on the web where I post some stuff
    376 </a><a href="#h4-0-153" id="h4-0-153" class="i">+            that I learn over the years, book recommendations, and logs from the
    377 </a><a href="#h4-0-154" id="h4-0-154" class="i">+            gym exercises.
    378 </a><a href="#h4-0-155" id="h4-0-155" class="i">+          &lt;/p&gt;
    379 </a><a href="#h4-0-156" id="h4-0-156" class="i">+          &lt;p&gt;
    380 </a><a href="#h4-0-157" id="h4-0-157" class="i">+            This website will be constantly changing over time and that&#39;s funny.
    381 </a><a href="#h4-0-158" id="h4-0-158" class="i">+          &lt;/p&gt;
    382 </a><a href="#h4-0-159" id="h4-0-159" class="i">+          &lt;p&gt;
    383 </a><a href="#h4-0-160" id="h4-0-160" class="i">+            Right now, I&#39;m working with Design Systems and making the web
    384 </a><a href="#h4-0-161" id="h4-0-161" class="i">+            accessible for everyone.
    385 </a><a href="#h4-0-162" id="h4-0-162" class="i">+          &lt;/p&gt;

    391 </a><a href="#h4-0-168" id="h4-0-168" class="i">+            front-end developer. React is my bread and butter.
    392 </a><a href="#h4-0-169" id="h4-0-169" class="i">+          &lt;/p&gt;
    393 </a><a href="#h4-0-170" id="h4-0-170" class="i">+          &lt;p&gt;
    394 </a><a href="#h4-0-171" id="h4-0-171" class="i">+            I&#39;m part of the group of Developer Experience, our job to help
    395 </a><a href="#h4-0-172" id="h4-0-172" class="i">+            developers to make better software for our products.
    396 </a><a href="#h4-0-173" id="h4-0-173" class="i">+          &lt;/p&gt;

   2573 </a><a href="#h110-0-147" id="h110-0-147" class="i">+            &lt;section class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;
   2574 </a><a href="#h110-0-148" id="h110-0-148" class="i">+

   2576 </a><a href="#h110-0-150" id="h110-0-150" class="i">+  &lt;div class=&quot;[ page-content ]&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Hello, world! This is my first post ever made on this new site.&lt;/p&gt;
   2577 </a><a href="#h110-0-151" id="h110-0-151" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is the place where I&#39;m going to write about my life, my work, and my hobbies. The things that I want to save in a secure place instead of my head.&lt;/p&gt;
   2578 </a><a href="#h110-0-152" id="h110-0-152" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Why am I making this website and not using some other tool like medium?
   2579 </a><a href="#h110-0-153" id="h110-0-153" class="i">+Well, the first reason is... I don&#39;t know how to make a website so I&#39;m making this one.&lt;/p&gt;
   2580 </a><a href="#h110-0-154" id="h110-0-154" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The second reason is that I want control over the content of my posts and something very simple.
   2581 </a><a href="#h110-0-155" id="h110-0-155" class="i">+I don&#39;t want paywalls, ads, etc. It&#39;s just a blog, not a new NTF collection.&lt;/p&gt;
   2582 </a><a href="#h110-0-156" id="h110-0-156" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Well, maybe I&#39;ll add some ads in the future. &lt;strong&gt;That&#39;s a bad joke&lt;/strong&gt; please ignore it.&lt;/p&gt;
   2583 </a><a href="#h110-0-157" id="h110-0-157" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The next post will be about how I&#39;m making this website and the resources I&#39;m using.&lt;/p&gt;
   2584 </a><a href="#h110-0-158" id="h110-0-158" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;But if you&#39;re a little impatient, you can check out this &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/hectoraldairah/bitbyte-blog&quot;&gt;Github repo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   2585 </a><a href="#h110-0-159" id="h110-0-159" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I&#39;m using &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.11ty.dev/&quot;&gt;Eleventy&lt;/a&gt; btw.&lt;/p&gt;

   2587 </a><a href="#h110-0-161" id="h110-0-161" class="i">+You need to finish your shit before you start your next one. - IDK&lt;/p&gt;

   3138 </a><a href="#h112-0-149" id="h112-0-149" class="i">+&lt;article class=&quot;constrained&quot;&gt;
   3139 </a><a href="#h112-0-150" id="h112-0-150" class="i">+  &lt;div class=&quot;[ page-content ]&quot;&gt;&lt;h1 id=&quot;why-go%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Why Go? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#why-go%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3140 </a><a href="#h112-0-151" id="h112-0-151" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
   3141 </a><a href="#h112-0-152" id="h112-0-152" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;As I mentioned before here on my blog, one of my goals of new years eve is to learn more about back-end development  to [[Be a better Front-End Dev]].&lt;/p&gt;
   3142 </a><a href="#h112-0-153" id="h112-0-153" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;At my job, I already tried some back-end stuff with some languages:&lt;/p&gt;
   3143 </a><a href="#h112-0-154" id="h112-0-154" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   3144 </a><a href="#h112-0-155" id="h112-0-155" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Node.js aka Javascript&lt;/li&gt;
   3145 </a><a href="#h112-0-156" id="h112-0-156" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Python&lt;/li&gt;
   3146 </a><a href="#h112-0-157" id="h112-0-157" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Java... ewww&lt;/li&gt;
   3147 </a><a href="#h112-0-158" id="h112-0-158" class="i">+&lt;/ol&gt;
   3148 </a><a href="#h112-0-159" id="h112-0-159" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The first path that I take was using Node.js, the decision was very easy to me. I already knew [[Javascript]], so touching some  AWS Lambdas and Micro-Services at my Job wasn&#39;t every hard to follow and to commit something to production.&lt;/p&gt;
   3149 </a><a href="#h112-0-160" id="h112-0-160" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It is fine (I guess) but I wanted to learn other thing more that Javascript to expand my horizons.&lt;/p&gt;
   3150 </a><a href="#h112-0-161" id="h112-0-161" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Later on, I started to work with Python, that is not completely new for me. In some point of my early dev career, I tried Flask to develop a simple REST API. It was very fun but not so much appealing for me to keep me in that way of back-end development.&lt;/p&gt;
   3151 </a><a href="#h112-0-162" id="h112-0-162" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Thank god that the projects that I&#39;ve been working at my job are very well designed and with good project structure. Even the test are very simple straightforward to follow. Committing a new feature for production? GG izi.&lt;/p&gt;
   3152 </a><a href="#h112-0-163" id="h112-0-163" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Python is fun, I enjoyed PyTest so much, even more than some unit test tools in Javascript, but at the end of the day I think that I need to learn some &lt;strong&gt;REAL&lt;/strong&gt; back-end language.&lt;/p&gt;
   3153 </a><a href="#h112-0-164" id="h112-0-164" class="i">+&lt;blockquote&gt;
   3154 </a><a href="#h112-0-165" id="h112-0-165" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The &amp;quot;REAL&amp;quot; word that I use before it refers better to &amp;quot;learn a compiled language&amp;quot; or some &amp;quot;blazingly fast language&amp;quot;. Don&#39;t be so judgy, please.&lt;/p&gt;
   3155 </a><a href="#h112-0-166" id="h112-0-166" class="i">+&lt;/blockquote&gt;
   3156 </a><a href="#h112-0-167" id="h112-0-167" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;So Go was on my eye for a while. I watched a lot of videos about on Youtube and gives me a lot of good  impressions:&lt;/p&gt;
   3157 </a><a href="#h112-0-168" id="h112-0-168" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   3158 </a><a href="#h112-0-169" id="h112-0-169" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;The syntax is very well designed and elegant&lt;/li&gt;
   3159 </a><a href="#h112-0-170" id="h112-0-170" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;It is  compiled language (blazingly fast)&lt;/li&gt;
   3160 </a><a href="#h112-0-171" id="h112-0-171" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Strongly type&lt;/li&gt;
   3161 </a><a href="#h112-0-172" id="h112-0-172" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Good documentation&lt;/li&gt;
   3162 </a><a href="#h112-0-173" id="h112-0-173" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;High employability&lt;/li&gt;
   3163 </a><a href="#h112-0-174" id="h112-0-174" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Fun&lt;/li&gt;
   3164 </a><a href="#h112-0-175" id="h112-0-175" class="i">+&lt;/ol&gt;
   3165 </a><a href="#h112-0-176" id="h112-0-176" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;why-not-java%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Why not Java? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#why-not-java%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3166 </a><a href="#h112-0-177" id="h112-0-177" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   3167 </a><a href="#h112-0-178" id="h112-0-178" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Ewww.&lt;/p&gt;
   3168 </a><a href="#h112-0-179" id="h112-0-179" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;how-i-started%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;How I started? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#how-i-started%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3169 </a><a href="#h112-0-180" id="h112-0-180" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   3170 </a><a href="#h112-0-181" id="h112-0-181" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I highly recommend to check to &lt;a href=&quot;https://go.dev/doc/effective_go&quot;&gt;official documentation&lt;/a&gt; first. It&#39;s every well written, almost well enough as the Elixir documentation &lt;em&gt;chef kiss emoji&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
   3171 </a><a href="#h112-0-182" id="h112-0-182" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Next, you can GO (get it? hahaha :c ) to this next resources:&lt;/p&gt;
   3172 </a><a href="#h112-0-183" id="h112-0-183" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   3173 </a><a href="#h112-0-184" id="h112-0-184" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://exercism.org/tracks/go&quot;&gt;Go in Exercism&lt;/a&gt;: This is my first option when I need to learn some new programming language&lt;/li&gt;
   3174 </a><a href="#h112-0-185" id="h112-0-185" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.boot.dev/tracks/backend&quot;&gt;Boot.dev Go Course&lt;/a&gt;: Very fun and easy to follow&lt;/li&gt;
   3175 </a><a href="#h112-0-186" id="h112-0-186" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://100go.co/&quot;&gt;100 Go Mistakes and How to Avoid Them&lt;/a&gt;: This is fucking great and very useful when you want to make the things right.&lt;/li&gt;
   3176 </a><a href="#h112-0-187" id="h112-0-187" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://gophercises.com/&quot;&gt;Gophercises&lt;/a&gt; : Imagine a gym but for learning Go, that&#39;s right.&lt;/li&gt;
   3177 </a><a href="#h112-0-188" id="h112-0-188" class="i">+&lt;/ol&gt;
   3178 </a><a href="#h112-0-189" id="h112-0-189" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Later on I started to building something for and by myself. I&#39;m working in a very simple CLI program to publish my Obsidian notes here on the blog and a Pokemon project... shhh is secret for now.&lt;/p&gt;
   3179 </a><a href="#h112-0-190" id="h112-0-190" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;do-you-expect-something-more%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Do you expect something more? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#do-you-expect-something-more%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3180 </a><a href="#h112-0-191" id="h112-0-191" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   3181 </a><a href="#h112-0-192" id="h112-0-192" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I&#39;m very new to Go so I can&#39;t offer new ways for learning it, what I can offer you is a very well respected Youtube channels to continue with your journey&lt;/p&gt;
   3182 </a><a href="#h112-0-193" id="h112-0-193" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   3183 </a><a href="#h112-0-194" id="h112-0-194" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/@bashbunni&quot;&gt;Bashbunni&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;

   3186 </a><a href="#h112-0-197" id="h112-0-197" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/@dreamsofcode&quot;&gt;Should you learn Go in 2023?&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
   3187 </a><a href="#h112-0-198" id="h112-0-198" class="i">+&lt;/ol&gt;

   3587 </a><a href="#h114-0-129" id="h114-0-129" class="i">+  &lt;h3&gt;My nvim config 2022&lt;/h3&gt;
   3588 </a><a href="#h114-0-130" id="h114-0-130" class="i">+  
   3589 </a><a href="#h114-0-131" id="h114-0-131" class="i">+   &lt;h4&gt;A collection of plugins that I use for nvim  ::  &lt;time style=&quot;font-size: 14px&quot; datetime=&quot;Aug 5, 2022&quot;&gt;Aug 5, 2022&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;  
   3590 </a><a href="#h114-0-132" id="h114-0-132" class="i">+  &lt;/div&gt;
   3591 </a><a href="#h114-0-133" id="h114-0-133" class="i">+
   3592 </a><a href="#h114-0-134" id="h114-0-134" class="i">+
   3593 </a><a href="#h114-0-135" id="h114-0-135" class="i">+
   3594 </a><a href="#h114-0-136" id="h114-0-136" class="i">+&lt;ul class=&quot;[ tag-list ]&quot; aria-describedby=&quot;tags-desc&quot;&gt;
   3595 </a><a href="#h114-0-137" id="h114-0-137" class="i">+  
   3596 </a><a href="#h114-0-138" id="h114-0-138" class="i">+  &lt;li&gt;
   3597 </a><a href="#h114-0-139" id="h114-0-139" class="i">+    &lt;a href=&quot;/tag/nvim/&quot;&gt;#Nvim&lt;/a&gt;
   3598 </a><a href="#h114-0-140" id="h114-0-140" class="i">+  &lt;/li&gt;
   3599 </a><a href="#h114-0-141" id="h114-0-141" class="i">+  
   3600 </a><a href="#h114-0-142" id="h114-0-142" class="i">+  &lt;li&gt;
   3601 </a><a href="#h114-0-143" id="h114-0-143" class="i">+    &lt;a href=&quot;/tag/tools/&quot;&gt;#Tools&lt;/a&gt;
   3602 </a><a href="#h114-0-144" id="h114-0-144" class="i">+  &lt;/li&gt;
   3603 </a><a href="#h114-0-145" id="h114-0-145" class="i">+  
   3604 </a><a href="#h114-0-146" id="h114-0-146" class="i">+  &lt;li&gt;
   3605 </a><a href="#h114-0-147" id="h114-0-147" class="i">+    &lt;a href=&quot;/tag/programming/&quot;&gt;#Programming&lt;/a&gt;
   3606 </a><a href="#h114-0-148" id="h114-0-148" class="i">+  &lt;/li&gt;
   3607 </a><a href="#h114-0-149" id="h114-0-149" class="i">+  
   3608 </a><a href="#h114-0-150" id="h114-0-150" class="i">+&lt;/ul&gt;
   3609 </a><a href="#h114-0-151" id="h114-0-151" class="i">+
   3610 </a><a href="#h114-0-152" id="h114-0-152" class="i">+&lt;/div&gt;
   3611 </a><a href="#h114-0-153" id="h114-0-153" class="i">+
   3612 </a><a href="#h114-0-154" id="h114-0-154" class="i">+        &lt;main tabindex=&quot;-1&quot; id=&quot;main-content&quot; class=&quot;[ main-content ]&quot;&gt;
   3613 </a><a href="#h114-0-155" id="h114-0-155" class="i">+            &lt;section class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;
   3614 </a><a href="#h114-0-156" id="h114-0-156" class="i">+             
   3615 </a><a href="#h114-0-157" id="h114-0-157" class="i">+&lt;article class=&quot;constrained&quot;&gt;
   3616 </a><a href="#h114-0-158" id="h114-0-158" class="i">+  &lt;div class=&quot;[ page-content ]&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;I&#39;ve been using the vim/nvim ecosystem for more than a year and I just love it.
   3617 </a><a href="#h114-0-159" id="h114-0-159" class="i">+Using NVIM improved my workflow so much after I learned the basics of it and how to properly create a base configuration.&lt;/p&gt;
   3618 </a><a href="#h114-0-160" id="h114-0-160" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s not so much hard to use despite the &lt;strong&gt;insanely amount&lt;/strong&gt; of memes on Twitter. Please, stop with the exit vim joke is not funny anymore.
   3619 </a><a href="#h114-0-161" id="h114-0-161" class="i">+&lt;br&gt;
   3620 </a><a href="#h114-0-162" id="h114-0-162" class="i">+I&#39;ll write a post about some programming jokes that aged like milk.&lt;/p&gt;
   3621 </a><a href="#h114-0-163" id="h114-0-163" class="i">+&lt;h2 id=&quot;lua-is-love-%E2%99%A1&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Lua is love  &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#lua-is-love-%E2%99%A1&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3622 </a><a href="#h114-0-164" id="h114-0-164" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
   3623 </a><a href="#h114-0-165" id="h114-0-165" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;VIM comes with a config file, typically the .vimrc that is written in vimscript.
   3624 </a><a href="#h114-0-166" id="h114-0-166" class="i">+Even though, is not that bad. I find it difficult to manually configure and the .vimrc file becomes so big if you add a lot of plugins to try.&lt;/p&gt;
   3625 </a><a href="#h114-0-167" id="h114-0-167" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;NVIM uses Lua as an alternative to configuring nvim. It&#39;s a very easy programming language, you can learn the basics in a week and start using it with that, you can create a more organized structure to save your plugins and config files.
   3626 </a><a href="#h114-0-168" id="h114-0-168" class="i">+Another advantage to using Lua is the community around it.&lt;/p&gt;
   3627 </a><a href="#h114-0-169" id="h114-0-169" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A lot of new plugins for nvim are written on Lua, making it faster than other languages like JavaScript.&lt;/p&gt;
   3628 </a><a href="#h114-0-170" id="h114-0-170" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Also, making my NVIM config modular helps &lt;strong&gt;a lot&lt;/strong&gt; with the organization of everything.&lt;/p&gt;
   3629 </a><a href="#h114-0-171" id="h114-0-171" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Next, I&#39;m gonna tell you what plugins I use the most.&lt;/p&gt;
   3630 </a><a href="#h114-0-172" id="h114-0-172" class="i">+&lt;h2 id=&quot;most-have-plugins&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Most Have Plugins &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#most-have-plugins&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3631 </a><a href="#h114-0-173" id="h114-0-173" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
   3632 </a><a href="#h114-0-174" id="h114-0-174" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This plugins are a must if you wanna improve you NVIM experience.&lt;/p&gt;
   3633 </a><a href="#h114-0-175" id="h114-0-175" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;telescope&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Telescope &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#telescope&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3634 </a><a href="#h114-0-176" id="h114-0-176" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   3635 </a><a href="#h114-0-177" id="h114-0-177" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is one of the plugins I use the most, one of the best fuzzy finders around here.&lt;/p&gt;
   3636 </a><a href="#h114-0-178" id="h114-0-178" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I like how fast it is and a lot of the options that you can configure with it. Search by file or by a regex expression with a nice UI and a lot of color-schemes are supported.&lt;/p&gt;
   3637 </a><a href="#h114-0-179" id="h114-0-179" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../../assets/images/tele.gif&quot; alt=&quot;telescope&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3638 </a><a href="#h114-0-180" id="h114-0-180" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/nvim-telescope/telescope.nvim&quot;&gt;Telescope plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3639 </a><a href="#h114-0-181" id="h114-0-181" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;nvim-tree&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;nvim-tree &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#nvim-tree&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3640 </a><a href="#h114-0-182" id="h114-0-182" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   3641 </a><a href="#h114-0-183" id="h114-0-183" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I see it as the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/preservim/nerdtree&quot;&gt;NERDTree&lt;/a&gt; improved, very light and blazingly fast.
   3642 </a><a href="#h114-0-184" id="h114-0-184" class="i">+You can use web-dev-icons. Extremely configurable but no overwhelming.&lt;/p&gt;
   3643 </a><a href="#h114-0-185" id="h114-0-185" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s easy to learn all the keybindings, wanna add a new file? Just type a, edit? e, open? o. So simple and intuitive&lt;/p&gt;
   3644 </a><a href="#h114-0-186" id="h114-0-186" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../../assets/images/nvimtree.gif&quot; alt=&quot;telescope&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3645 </a><a href="#h114-0-187" id="h114-0-187" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/kyazdani42/nvim-tree.lua&quot;&gt;nvim-tree plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3646 </a><a href="#h114-0-188" id="h114-0-188" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;nvim-tree-sitter&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;nvim-tree-sitter &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#nvim-tree-sitter&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3647 </a><a href="#h114-0-189" id="h114-0-189" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   3648 </a><a href="#h114-0-190" id="h114-0-190" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Tree sitter it&#39;s a parser generator for our code in order to nvim can understand our code.
   3649 </a><a href="#h114-0-191" id="h114-0-191" class="i">+This is very helpful because you can have a lot of cool features for your favorite programming language, like: syntax highlight, folding, text-object manipulation, etc.&lt;/p&gt;
   3650 </a><a href="#h114-0-192" id="h114-0-192" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The list of supported languages is huge and a lot of new features are being added to nvim.&lt;/p&gt;
   3651 </a><a href="#h114-0-193" id="h114-0-193" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter&quot;&gt;nvim-tree-sitter plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3652 </a><a href="#h114-0-194" id="h114-0-194" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;float-term&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Float Term &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#float-term&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3653 </a><a href="#h114-0-195" id="h114-0-195" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   3654 </a><a href="#h114-0-196" id="h114-0-196" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is one has increased my productivity a lot. Instead of open a new terminal somewhere else of changing between spaces
   3655 </a><a href="#h114-0-197" id="h114-0-197" class="i">+I just open a new float term. Float term is just a terminal but... floating in your nvim space.&lt;/p&gt;
   3656 </a><a href="#h114-0-198" id="h114-0-198" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;You can have a lot of float terms opened but one is just enough for me. The easy access is hot.&lt;/p&gt;
   3657 </a><a href="#h114-0-199" id="h114-0-199" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../../assets/images/floatterm.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Float Term&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3658 </a><a href="#h114-0-200" id="h114-0-200" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/voldikss/vim-floaterm&quot;&gt;Float Term plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3659 </a><a href="#h114-0-201" id="h114-0-201" class="i">+&lt;h2 id=&quot;more-plugins&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;More plugins &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;#more-plugins&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   3660 </a><a href="#h114-0-202" id="h114-0-202" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
   3661 </a><a href="#h114-0-203" id="h114-0-203" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Those are my most &amp;quot;showy&amp;quot; plugins. I use a lot more but are just for tiny things like color colorizer, lsp config, color-schemes, etc.
   3662 </a><a href="#h114-0-204" id="h114-0-204" class="i">+I strongly suggest that you vim config should be minimal as you can to get a faster start and use Lua instead of vimrc. This will make your
   3663 </a><a href="#h114-0-205" id="h114-0-205" class="i">+life easier and happier.&lt;/p&gt;
   3664 </a><a href="#h114-0-206" id="h114-0-206" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;If you wanna see all my nvim config you can check my repo
   3665 </a><a href="#h114-0-207" id="h114-0-207" class="i">+&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/hectoraldairah/nvim-config&quot;&gt;nvim configuration&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   3666 </a><a href="#h114-0-208" id="h114-0-208" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s not that fancy so maybe you can understand everything there.&lt;/p&gt;
   3667 </a><a href="#h114-0-209" id="h114-0-209" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Well, that it! I know for sure that this plugins list will be changing over time but I will stay with the philosphy of less is more&lt;/p&gt;
   3668 </a><a href="#h114-0-210" id="h114-0-210" class="i">+&lt;/div&gt;

   3855 </a><a href="#h115-0-130" id="h115-0-130" class="i">+  
   3856 </a><a href="#h115-0-131" id="h115-0-131" class="i">+   &lt;h4&gt;I don&amp;#39;t belive you  ::  &lt;time style=&quot;font-size: 14px&quot; datetime=&quot;Apr 12, 2023&quot;&gt;Apr 12, 2023&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;

   3862 </a><a href="#h115-0-137" id="h115-0-137" class="i">+  
   3863 </a><a href="#h115-0-138" id="h115-0-138" class="i">+  &lt;li&gt;

   3871 </a><a href="#h115-0-146" id="h115-0-146" class="i">+        &lt;main tabindex=&quot;-1&quot; id=&quot;main-content&quot; class=&quot;[ main-content ]&quot;&gt;
   3872 </a><a href="#h115-0-147" id="h115-0-147" class="i">+            &lt;section class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;
   3873 </a><a href="#h115-0-148" id="h115-0-148" class="i">+             
   3874 </a><a href="#h115-0-149" id="h115-0-149" class="i">+&lt;article class=&quot;constrained&quot;&gt;
   3875 </a><a href="#h115-0-150" id="h115-0-150" class="i">+  &lt;div class=&quot;[ page-content ]&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Have you ever seen this legend in a lot of websites? It&#39;s ALWAYS in the footer of a web page.&lt;/p&gt;
   3876 </a><a href="#h115-0-151" id="h115-0-151" class="i">+&lt;blockquote&gt;
   3877 </a><a href="#h115-0-152" id="h115-0-152" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Made with  and (coffee, mushrooms, sugar, etc)&lt;/p&gt;
   3878 </a><a href="#h115-0-153" id="h115-0-153" class="i">+&lt;/blockquote&gt;
   3879 </a><a href="#h115-0-154" id="h115-0-154" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Even I use to have it in my old sites.&lt;/p&gt;
   3880 </a><a href="#h115-0-155" id="h115-0-155" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A was thinking about it. It&#39;s kind of weird, isn&#39;t? It&#39;s kinda like a meme of web-development.&lt;/p&gt;
   3881 </a><a href="#h115-0-156" id="h115-0-156" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;No one knows where this trend began and I think that is very hard to know it,
   3882 </a><a href="#h115-0-157" id="h115-0-157" class="i">+there is no metrics for this (maybe because it doesn&#39;t matter).&lt;/p&gt;
   3883 </a><a href="#h115-0-158" id="h115-0-158" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I think this is a LIE, yes a very hard lie to tell to our users. Ok, ok, I&#39;m not judging your love and dedication for
   3884 </a><a href="#h115-0-159" id="h115-0-159" class="i">+your site. I think is just a &lt;em&gt;cliche&lt;/em&gt; and very burned by now.&lt;/p&gt;

   3926 </a><a href="#h115-0-201" id="h115-0-201" class="i">+document.addEventListener(&#39;DOMContentLoaded&#39;, (event) =&gt; {
   3927 </a><a href="#h115-0-202" id="h115-0-202" class="i">+
   3928 </a><a href="#h115-0-203" id="h115-0-203" class="i">+  const focusSound = new Audio(&#39;../../assets/sounds/Beep 99630.mp3&#39;);
   3929 </a><a href="#h115-0-204" id="h115-0-204" class="i">+  focusSound.preload = &#39;auto&#39;;
   3930 </a><a href="#h115-0-205" id="h115-0-205" class="i">+
   3931 </a><a href="#h115-0-206" id="h115-0-206" class="i">+ const playFocusSound = () =&gt; {

   4071 </a><a href="#h116-0-129" id="h116-0-129" class="i">+  &lt;h3&gt;Things I want to learn on 2022&lt;/h3&gt;
   4072 </a><a href="#h116-0-130" id="h116-0-130" class="i">+  
   4073 </a><a href="#h116-0-131" id="h116-0-131" class="i">+   &lt;h4&gt;Some things that catch my attention and I want to learn on 2022.  ::  &lt;time style=&quot;font-size: 14px&quot; datetime=&quot;Dec 30, 2021&quot;&gt;Dec 30, 2021&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;  
   4074 </a><a href="#h116-0-132" id="h116-0-132" class="i">+  &lt;/div&gt;
   4075 </a><a href="#h116-0-133" id="h116-0-133" class="i">+
   4076 </a><a href="#h116-0-134" id="h116-0-134" class="i">+
   4077 </a><a href="#h116-0-135" id="h116-0-135" class="i">+
   4078 </a><a href="#h116-0-136" id="h116-0-136" class="i">+&lt;ul class=&quot;[ tag-list ]&quot; aria-describedby=&quot;tags-desc&quot;&gt;
   4079 </a><a href="#h116-0-137" id="h116-0-137" class="i">+  
   4080 </a><a href="#h116-0-138" id="h116-0-138" class="i">+  &lt;li&gt;
   4081 </a><a href="#h116-0-139" id="h116-0-139" class="i">+    &lt;a href=&quot;/tag/personal/&quot;&gt;#Personal&lt;/a&gt;
   4082 </a><a href="#h116-0-140" id="h116-0-140" class="i">+  &lt;/li&gt;
   4083 </a><a href="#h116-0-141" id="h116-0-141" class="i">+  
   4084 </a><a href="#h116-0-142" id="h116-0-142" class="i">+&lt;/ul&gt;
   4085 </a><a href="#h116-0-143" id="h116-0-143" class="i">+
   4086 </a><a href="#h116-0-144" id="h116-0-144" class="i">+&lt;/div&gt;
   4087 </a><a href="#h116-0-145" id="h116-0-145" class="i">+
   4088 </a><a href="#h116-0-146" id="h116-0-146" class="i">+        &lt;main tabindex=&quot;-1&quot; id=&quot;main-content&quot; class=&quot;[ main-content ]&quot;&gt;
   4089 </a><a href="#h116-0-147" id="h116-0-147" class="i">+            &lt;section class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;
   4090 </a><a href="#h116-0-148" id="h116-0-148" class="i">+             
   4091 </a><a href="#h116-0-149" id="h116-0-149" class="i">+&lt;article class=&quot;constrained&quot;&gt;
   4092 </a><a href="#h116-0-150" id="h116-0-150" class="i">+  &lt;div class=&quot;[ page-content ]&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s the end of the year, and I&#39;m starting to think about what I want to learn in 2022.&lt;/p&gt;
   4093 </a><a href="#h116-0-151" id="h116-0-151" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   4094 </a><a href="#h116-0-152" id="h116-0-152" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4095 </a><a href="#h116-0-153" id="h116-0-153" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A new programming language: I&#39;m thinking on Clojure, Elm, or Elixir. I need to understand better the concepts of functional programming and how to use them. Maybe I&#39;ll use this expertise to apply javascript.&lt;/p&gt;
   4096 </a><a href="#h116-0-154" id="h116-0-154" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4097 </a><a href="#h116-0-155" id="h116-0-155" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4098 </a><a href="#h116-0-156" id="h116-0-156" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A new pixel art tool: I used to work with Photoshop and Adobe Flash to make pixel art animations, but I don&#39;t want to use them anymore (I can&#39;t run any Adobe App now) so I&#39;m thinking to use &lt;a href=&quot;https://aseprite.org&quot;&gt;aseprite&lt;/a&gt; because I did some basic animation with it two years ago.&lt;/p&gt;
   4099 </a><a href="#h116-0-157" id="h116-0-157" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4100 </a><a href="#h116-0-158" id="h116-0-158" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4101 </a><a href="#h116-0-159" id="h116-0-159" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Blender: I did some 3D animations when I was like 16? on an old mini laptop that I had. It was good at the time with only 2 Gb of ram but man, the software is getting ram expensive. Maybe I can start to make some things with my new computer.&lt;/p&gt;
   4102 </a><a href="#h116-0-160" id="h116-0-160" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4103 </a><a href="#h116-0-161" id="h116-0-161" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4104 </a><a href="#h116-0-162" id="h116-0-162" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;How to talk in public: Since 2019, I get the interest to do talks about tech with one cup of acid humor on it. The pandemic was a big problem here because there are no more live meetups and I just forget about it. With the online meetups, I can feel a chance to do it.&lt;/p&gt;
   4105 </a><a href="#h116-0-163" id="h116-0-163" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4106 </a><a href="#h116-0-164" id="h116-0-164" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4107 </a><a href="#h116-0-165" id="h116-0-165" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Back-end: Well, maybe this is kind of huge for me. I&#39;ve been doing front-end stuff for a while and my backend skills are getting pretty bad. My experience working with &lt;a href=&quot;https://expressjs.com/es/&quot;&gt;Express&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://adonisjs.com/&quot;&gt;Adonis&lt;/a&gt; was pretty good, but it was simple things. I don&#39;t know anything about databases too. So, yeah. Maybe I&#39;ll buy a course from &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.udemy.com/&quot;&gt;Udemy&lt;/a&gt; for it.&lt;/p&gt;
   4108 </a><a href="#h116-0-166" id="h116-0-166" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4109 </a><a href="#h116-0-167" id="h116-0-167" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4110 </a><a href="#h116-0-168" id="h116-0-168" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;CSS Art: Yes, another art stuff. All the &lt;a href=&quot;https://codepen.io/tag/css-art&quot;&gt;beautiful CSS art that is on codepen&lt;/a&gt; makes me want to do something similar. I&#39;m not sure what exactly but some 3D CSS animations are on my eye.&lt;/p&gt;
   4111 </a><a href="#h116-0-169" id="h116-0-169" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4112 </a><a href="#h116-0-170" id="h116-0-170" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4113 </a><a href="#h116-0-171" id="h116-0-171" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Being fluent in Esperanto and learning more about romantic languages: Duolingo and &lt;a href=&quot;https://lernu.net/&quot;&gt;Lernu&lt;/a&gt; are my best friends here.&lt;/p&gt;

   4540 </a><a href="#h119-0-146" id="h119-0-146" class="i">+
   4541 </a><a href="#h119-0-147" id="h119-0-147" class="i">+  &lt;div class=&quot;[ page-content ]&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is my first time reading Haruki Murakami. I&#39;ve heard a lot of good things about this book so I give it a try.&lt;/p&gt;
   4542 </a><a href="#h119-0-148" id="h119-0-148" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;picture&gt;&lt;source type=&quot;image/webp&quot; srcset=&quot;/assets/images/X6dDraD6h8-400.webp 400w&quot; sizes=&quot;100vw&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Tokio Blues Cover&quot; class=&quot;Tiokio Blues Cover&quot; loading=&quot;lazy&quot; decoding=&quot;async&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/X6dDraD6h8-400.jpeg&quot; width=&quot;400&quot; height=&quot;618&quot;&gt;&lt;/picture&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4543 </a><a href="#h119-0-149" id="h119-0-149" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The book is really good in terms of story-telling, every detail such as time, places, people description, and even food is very well written. You can imagine very easily all the environments that Murakami presents and keep following the story, a very easy lecture.&lt;/p&gt;
   4544 </a><a href="#h119-0-150" id="h119-0-150" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The book sadly doesn&#39;t contain so many references to the Japan of the era, just very few hints of social and political change and people&#39;s behavior rather a bunch of very good song&#39;s that you can find on Spotify that follow the protagonist and his friends?&lt;/p&gt;
   4545 </a><a href="#h119-0-151" id="h119-0-151" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I said friends? &#39;cause I think the protagonist is just keeping relations with everyone just for not to be alone rather than being purely friendly. This is just for the case of men, if you&#39;re a woman in this book, is very sure that you will be sexualized even for the smallest things.&lt;/p&gt;
   4546 </a><a href="#h119-0-152" id="h119-0-152" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Maybe is a reflection of the writer, the all I want I get protagonist and the Japan of the era.&lt;/p&gt;
   4547 </a><a href="#h119-0-153" id="h119-0-153" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I&#39;m not sure if I want to read more from Murakami. Maybe later.&lt;/p&gt;

   4677 </a><a href="#h122-0-47" id="h122-0-47" class="i">+      &lt;![CDATA[ &lt;p&gt;So, in order to get better at making pixel art I started to get into tutorials for learning.&lt;/p&gt;
   4678 </a><a href="#h122-0-48" id="h122-0-48" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;For now, my first learning source was Youtube. I started to watch a lot of pixelart art channels for begginer tips and tricks to start making my first compositions.&lt;/p&gt;
   4679 </a><a href="#h122-0-49" id="h122-0-49" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;One thing I learned is not to start making big pixelarts canvas, instead you can start with a 8x8 canvas. It&#39;s more easier to create very little drawings and you have more control about space and colors.&lt;/p&gt;
   4680 </a><a href="#h122-0-50" id="h122-0-50" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is my first composition, its like a Mario&#39;s Ghost but witk a pink ink. This drawing has very little variations (same color but different shades) to start making shadows and lights.&lt;/p&gt;
   4681 </a><a href="#h122-0-51" id="h122-0-51" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I think it&#39;s pretty good just for my first (real) attemp.&lt;/p&gt;
   4682 </a><a href="#h122-0-52" id="h122-0-52" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/pixelart/strawberry-boo/ice-cream-ghost.png&quot; alt=&quot;Strawberry Ghost&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

   4690 </a><a href="#h122-0-60" id="h122-0-60" class="i">+    &lt;id&gt;https://bitbyte.blog/pixelart/ghost-love/&lt;/id&gt;

   4692 </a><a href="#h122-0-62" id="h122-0-62" class="i">+      &lt;![CDATA[ &lt;p&gt;Pixelart is my favorite style for videogames. Why?&lt;/p&gt;
   4693 </a><a href="#h122-0-63" id="h122-0-63" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;When I was a child, I had only three videogame consoles; the ps1, ps2 and the GBA.&lt;/p&gt;
   4694 </a><a href="#h122-0-64" id="h122-0-64" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I missed a lot of &amp;quot;new&amp;quot; games until I got a PC and I started to play more &amp;quot;new&amp;quot; games.
   4695 </a><a href="#h122-0-65" id="h122-0-65" class="i">+Even then, the PC was an old mini-laptop with only 2 GB of RAM.&lt;/p&gt;
   4696 </a><a href="#h122-0-66" id="h122-0-66" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;That&#39;s the reason I used to play emulators for the SNES, Gameboy and GBA and I fall in
   4697 </a><a href="#h122-0-67" id="h122-0-67" class="i">+love with the retro style.&lt;/p&gt;
   4698 </a><a href="#h122-0-68" id="h122-0-68" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;As you can see on this website, I like the pixelart style. So, why not start to making it?&lt;/p&gt;
   4699 </a><a href="#h122-0-69" id="h122-0-69" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I always think I&#39;m not an &lt;strong&gt;artsy boy&lt;/strong&gt;. I have zero art skills... I don&#39;t like that.&lt;/p&gt;
   4700 </a><a href="#h122-0-70" id="h122-0-70" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;That&#39;s why I started with pixelart. The &lt;em&gt;i love the retro style&lt;/em&gt; + &lt;em&gt;i wanna make some art that doesn&#39;t suck&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4701 </a><a href="#h122-0-71" id="h122-0-71" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;That boring introduction was for this little guy.&lt;/p&gt;
   4702 </a><a href="#h122-0-72" id="h122-0-72" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;My first pixel art ever made.&lt;/p&gt;
   4703 </a><a href="#h122-0-73" id="h122-0-73" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/pixelart/ghost-love/ghost-love.png&quot; alt=&quot;Spooky Ghost&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4704 </a><a href="#h122-0-74" id="h122-0-74" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This was made with &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.aseprite.org/&quot;&gt;Asperite&lt;/a&gt; and just a little bit of time.&lt;/p&gt;
   4705 </a><a href="#h122-0-75" id="h122-0-75" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It was made on the fly, and the color palette I chose was random.&lt;/p&gt;
   4706 </a><a href="#h122-0-76" id="h122-0-76" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I don&#39;t remember the canvas size.&lt;/p&gt;
   4707 </a><a href="#h122-0-77" id="h122-0-77" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Ghost Love makes me happy because it&#39;s a reminder that I can make art.&lt;/p&gt;

   4713 </a><a href="#h122-0-83" id="h122-0-83" class="i">+    &lt;link href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/learning-go-a-new-adventure/&quot; /&gt;
   4714 </a><a href="#h122-0-84" id="h122-0-84" class="i">+    &lt;updated&gt;2024-01-07T00:00:00Z&lt;/updated&gt;
   4715 </a><a href="#h122-0-85" id="h122-0-85" class="i">+    &lt;id&gt;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/learning-go-a-new-adventure/&lt;/id&gt;
   4716 </a><a href="#h122-0-86" id="h122-0-86" class="i">+    &lt;content type=&quot;html&quot;&gt;
   4717 </a><a href="#h122-0-87" id="h122-0-87" class="i">+      &lt;![CDATA[ &lt;h1 id=&quot;why-go%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Why Go? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/learning-go-a-new-adventure/#why-go%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4718 </a><a href="#h122-0-88" id="h122-0-88" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
   4719 </a><a href="#h122-0-89" id="h122-0-89" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;As I mentioned before here on my blog, one of my goals of new years eve is to learn more about back-end development  to [[Be a better Front-End Dev]].&lt;/p&gt;
   4720 </a><a href="#h122-0-90" id="h122-0-90" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;At my job, I already tried some back-end stuff with some languages:&lt;/p&gt;
   4721 </a><a href="#h122-0-91" id="h122-0-91" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   4722 </a><a href="#h122-0-92" id="h122-0-92" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Node.js aka Javascript&lt;/li&gt;
   4723 </a><a href="#h122-0-93" id="h122-0-93" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Python&lt;/li&gt;
   4724 </a><a href="#h122-0-94" id="h122-0-94" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Java... ewww&lt;/li&gt;
   4725 </a><a href="#h122-0-95" id="h122-0-95" class="i">+&lt;/ol&gt;
   4726 </a><a href="#h122-0-96" id="h122-0-96" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The first path that I take was using Node.js, the decision was very easy to me. I already knew [[Javascript]], so touching some  AWS Lambdas and Micro-Services at my Job wasn&#39;t every hard to follow and to commit something to production.&lt;/p&gt;
   4727 </a><a href="#h122-0-97" id="h122-0-97" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It is fine (I guess) but I wanted to learn other thing more that Javascript to expand my horizons.&lt;/p&gt;
   4728 </a><a href="#h122-0-98" id="h122-0-98" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Later on, I started to work with Python, that is not completely new for me. In some point of my early dev career, I tried Flask to develop a simple REST API. It was very fun but not so much appealing for me to keep me in that way of back-end development.&lt;/p&gt;
   4729 </a><a href="#h122-0-99" id="h122-0-99" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Thank god that the projects that I&#39;ve been working at my job are very well designed and with good project structure. Even the test are very simple straightforward to follow. Committing a new feature for production? GG izi.&lt;/p&gt;
   4730 </a><a href="#h122-0-100" id="h122-0-100" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Python is fun, I enjoyed PyTest so much, even more than some unit test tools in Javascript, but at the end of the day I think that I need to learn some &lt;strong&gt;REAL&lt;/strong&gt; back-end language.&lt;/p&gt;
   4731 </a><a href="#h122-0-101" id="h122-0-101" class="i">+&lt;blockquote&gt;
   4732 </a><a href="#h122-0-102" id="h122-0-102" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The &amp;quot;REAL&amp;quot; word that I use before it refers better to &amp;quot;learn a compiled language&amp;quot; or some &amp;quot;blazingly fast language&amp;quot;. Don&#39;t be so judgy, please.&lt;/p&gt;
   4733 </a><a href="#h122-0-103" id="h122-0-103" class="i">+&lt;/blockquote&gt;
   4734 </a><a href="#h122-0-104" id="h122-0-104" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;So Go was on my eye for a while. I watched a lot of videos about on Youtube and gives me a lot of good  impressions:&lt;/p&gt;
   4735 </a><a href="#h122-0-105" id="h122-0-105" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   4736 </a><a href="#h122-0-106" id="h122-0-106" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;The syntax is very well designed and elegant&lt;/li&gt;
   4737 </a><a href="#h122-0-107" id="h122-0-107" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;It is  compiled language (blazingly fast)&lt;/li&gt;
   4738 </a><a href="#h122-0-108" id="h122-0-108" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Strongly type&lt;/li&gt;
   4739 </a><a href="#h122-0-109" id="h122-0-109" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Good documentation&lt;/li&gt;
   4740 </a><a href="#h122-0-110" id="h122-0-110" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;High employability&lt;/li&gt;
   4741 </a><a href="#h122-0-111" id="h122-0-111" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;Fun&lt;/li&gt;
   4742 </a><a href="#h122-0-112" id="h122-0-112" class="i">+&lt;/ol&gt;
   4743 </a><a href="#h122-0-113" id="h122-0-113" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;why-not-java%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Why not Java? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/learning-go-a-new-adventure/#why-not-java%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;

   4748 </a><a href="#h122-0-118" id="h122-0-118" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I highly recommend to check to &lt;a href=&quot;https://go.dev/doc/effective_go&quot;&gt;official documentation&lt;/a&gt; first. It&#39;s every well written, almost well enough as the Elixir documentation &lt;em&gt;chef kiss emoji&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

   4757 </a><a href="#h122-0-127" id="h122-0-127" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;do-you-expect-something-more%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Do you expect something more? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/learning-go-a-new-adventure/#do-you-expect-something-more%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;

   4776 </a><a href="#h122-0-146" id="h122-0-146" class="i">+      &lt;![CDATA[ &lt;p&gt;Have you ever seen this legend in a lot of websites? It&#39;s ALWAYS in the footer of a web page.&lt;/p&gt;
   4777 </a><a href="#h122-0-147" id="h122-0-147" class="i">+&lt;blockquote&gt;
   4778 </a><a href="#h122-0-148" id="h122-0-148" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Made with  and (coffee, mushrooms, sugar, etc)&lt;/p&gt;
   4779 </a><a href="#h122-0-149" id="h122-0-149" class="i">+&lt;/blockquote&gt;
   4780 </a><a href="#h122-0-150" id="h122-0-150" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Even I use to have it in my old sites.&lt;/p&gt;
   4781 </a><a href="#h122-0-151" id="h122-0-151" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A was thinking about it. It&#39;s kind of weird, isn&#39;t? It&#39;s kinda like a meme of web-development.&lt;/p&gt;
   4782 </a><a href="#h122-0-152" id="h122-0-152" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;No one knows where this trend began and I think that is very hard to know it,
   4783 </a><a href="#h122-0-153" id="h122-0-153" class="i">+there is no metrics for this (maybe because it doesn&#39;t matter).&lt;/p&gt;
   4784 </a><a href="#h122-0-154" id="h122-0-154" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I think this is a LIE, yes a very hard lie to tell to our users. Ok, ok, I&#39;m not judging your love and dedication for
   4785 </a><a href="#h122-0-155" id="h122-0-155" class="i">+your site. I think is just a &lt;em&gt;cliche&lt;/em&gt; and very burned by now.&lt;/p&gt;

   4796 </a><a href="#h122-0-166" id="h122-0-166" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
   4797 </a><a href="#h122-0-167" id="h122-0-167" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;If you&#39;re very curious you already knew that I like to make some &lt;strong&gt;pixel art&lt;/strong&gt; in my free time (It&#39;s a very noble hobby btw) and learning new techniques for making my sprites less akward.&lt;/p&gt;
   4798 </a><a href="#h122-0-168" id="h122-0-168" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;In one of&lt;/p&gt;
   4799 </a><a href="#h122-0-169" id="h122-0-169" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Some have a beautifull desing, very cool animations, videos in the background or some kind of big interactive feature that makes the site stand-up.&lt;/p&gt;
   4800 </a><a href="#h122-0-170" id="h122-0-170" class="i">+&lt;h2 id=&quot;what-is-low-tech%3F&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;What is low-tech? &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/low-tech-websites-and-why-you-should-have-one-(maybe)/#what-is-low-tech%3F&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4801 </a><a href="#h122-0-171" id="h122-0-171" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
   4802 </a><a href="#h122-0-172" id="h122-0-172" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;header-3&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Header 3 &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/low-tech-websites-and-why-you-should-have-one-(maybe)/#header-3&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;

   4806 </a><a href="#h122-0-176" id="h122-0-176" class="i">+  &lt;/entry&gt;
   4807 </a><a href="#h122-0-177" id="h122-0-177" class="i">+  &lt;entry&gt;
   4808 </a><a href="#h122-0-178" id="h122-0-178" class="i">+    &lt;title&gt;My nvim config 2022&lt;/title&gt;
   4809 </a><a href="#h122-0-179" id="h122-0-179" class="i">+    &lt;link href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/&quot; /&gt;
   4810 </a><a href="#h122-0-180" id="h122-0-180" class="i">+    &lt;updated&gt;2022-08-06T00:00:00Z&lt;/updated&gt;
   4811 </a><a href="#h122-0-181" id="h122-0-181" class="i">+    &lt;id&gt;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/&lt;/id&gt;
   4812 </a><a href="#h122-0-182" id="h122-0-182" class="i">+    &lt;content type=&quot;html&quot;&gt;
   4813 </a><a href="#h122-0-183" id="h122-0-183" class="i">+      &lt;![CDATA[ &lt;p&gt;I&#39;ve been using the vim/nvim ecosystem for more than a year and I just love it.
   4814 </a><a href="#h122-0-184" id="h122-0-184" class="i">+Using NVIM improved my workflow so much after I learned the basics of it and how to properly create a base configuration.&lt;/p&gt;
   4815 </a><a href="#h122-0-185" id="h122-0-185" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s not so much hard to use despite the &lt;strong&gt;insanely amount&lt;/strong&gt; of memes on Twitter. Please, stop with the exit vim joke is not funny anymore.
   4816 </a><a href="#h122-0-186" id="h122-0-186" class="i">+&lt;br /&gt;
   4817 </a><a href="#h122-0-187" id="h122-0-187" class="i">+I&#39;ll write a post about some programming jokes that aged like milk.&lt;/p&gt;
   4818 </a><a href="#h122-0-188" id="h122-0-188" class="i">+&lt;h2 id=&quot;lua-is-love-%E2%99%A1&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Lua is love  &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/#lua-is-love-%E2%99%A1&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4819 </a><a href="#h122-0-189" id="h122-0-189" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
   4820 </a><a href="#h122-0-190" id="h122-0-190" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;VIM comes with a config file, typically the .vimrc that is written in vimscript.
   4821 </a><a href="#h122-0-191" id="h122-0-191" class="i">+Even though, is not that bad. I find it difficult to manually configure and the .vimrc file becomes so big if you add a lot of plugins to try.&lt;/p&gt;
   4822 </a><a href="#h122-0-192" id="h122-0-192" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;NVIM uses Lua as an alternative to configuring nvim. It&#39;s a very easy programming language, you can learn the basics in a week and start using it with that, you can create a more organized structure to save your plugins and config files.
   4823 </a><a href="#h122-0-193" id="h122-0-193" class="i">+Another advantage to using Lua is the community around it.&lt;/p&gt;
   4824 </a><a href="#h122-0-194" id="h122-0-194" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A lot of new plugins for nvim are written on Lua, making it faster than other languages like JavaScript.&lt;/p&gt;
   4825 </a><a href="#h122-0-195" id="h122-0-195" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Also, making my NVIM config modular helps &lt;strong&gt;a lot&lt;/strong&gt; with the organization of everything.&lt;/p&gt;
   4826 </a><a href="#h122-0-196" id="h122-0-196" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Next, I&#39;m gonna tell you what plugins I use the most.&lt;/p&gt;
   4827 </a><a href="#h122-0-197" id="h122-0-197" class="i">+&lt;h2 id=&quot;most-have-plugins&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Most Have Plugins &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/#most-have-plugins&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4828 </a><a href="#h122-0-198" id="h122-0-198" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
   4829 </a><a href="#h122-0-199" id="h122-0-199" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This plugins are a must if you wanna improve you NVIM experience.&lt;/p&gt;
   4830 </a><a href="#h122-0-200" id="h122-0-200" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;telescope&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Telescope &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/#telescope&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4831 </a><a href="#h122-0-201" id="h122-0-201" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   4832 </a><a href="#h122-0-202" id="h122-0-202" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is one of the plugins I use the most, one of the best fuzzy finders around here.&lt;/p&gt;
   4833 </a><a href="#h122-0-203" id="h122-0-203" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I like how fast it is and a lot of the options that you can configure with it. Search by file or by a regex expression with a nice UI and a lot of color-schemes are supported.&lt;/p&gt;
   4834 </a><a href="#h122-0-204" id="h122-0-204" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/assets/images/tele.gif&quot; alt=&quot;telescope&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4835 </a><a href="#h122-0-205" id="h122-0-205" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/nvim-telescope/telescope.nvim&quot;&gt;Telescope plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4836 </a><a href="#h122-0-206" id="h122-0-206" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;nvim-tree&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;nvim-tree &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/#nvim-tree&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4837 </a><a href="#h122-0-207" id="h122-0-207" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   4838 </a><a href="#h122-0-208" id="h122-0-208" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I see it as the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/preservim/nerdtree&quot;&gt;NERDTree&lt;/a&gt; improved, very light and blazingly fast.
   4839 </a><a href="#h122-0-209" id="h122-0-209" class="i">+You can use web-dev-icons. Extremely configurable but no overwhelming.&lt;/p&gt;
   4840 </a><a href="#h122-0-210" id="h122-0-210" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s easy to learn all the keybindings, wanna add a new file? Just type a, edit? e, open? o. So simple and intuitive&lt;/p&gt;
   4841 </a><a href="#h122-0-211" id="h122-0-211" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/assets/images/nvimtree.gif&quot; alt=&quot;telescope&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4842 </a><a href="#h122-0-212" id="h122-0-212" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/kyazdani42/nvim-tree.lua&quot;&gt;nvim-tree plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4843 </a><a href="#h122-0-213" id="h122-0-213" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;nvim-tree-sitter&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;nvim-tree-sitter &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/#nvim-tree-sitter&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4844 </a><a href="#h122-0-214" id="h122-0-214" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   4845 </a><a href="#h122-0-215" id="h122-0-215" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Tree sitter it&#39;s a parser generator for our code in order to nvim can understand our code.
   4846 </a><a href="#h122-0-216" id="h122-0-216" class="i">+This is very helpful because you can have a lot of cool features for your favorite programming language, like: syntax highlight, folding, text-object manipulation, etc.&lt;/p&gt;
   4847 </a><a href="#h122-0-217" id="h122-0-217" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The list of supported languages is huge and a lot of new features are being added to nvim.&lt;/p&gt;
   4848 </a><a href="#h122-0-218" id="h122-0-218" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter&quot;&gt;nvim-tree-sitter plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4849 </a><a href="#h122-0-219" id="h122-0-219" class="i">+&lt;h3 id=&quot;float-term&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;Float Term &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/#float-term&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4850 </a><a href="#h122-0-220" id="h122-0-220" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
   4851 </a><a href="#h122-0-221" id="h122-0-221" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is one has increased my productivity a lot. Instead of open a new terminal somewhere else of changing between spaces
   4852 </a><a href="#h122-0-222" id="h122-0-222" class="i">+I just open a new float term. Float term is just a terminal but... floating in your nvim space.&lt;/p&gt;
   4853 </a><a href="#h122-0-223" id="h122-0-223" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;You can have a lot of float terms opened but one is just enough for me. The easy access is hot.&lt;/p&gt;
   4854 </a><a href="#h122-0-224" id="h122-0-224" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/assets/images/floatterm.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Float Term&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4855 </a><a href="#h122-0-225" id="h122-0-225" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Try it: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/voldikss/vim-floaterm&quot;&gt;Float Term plugin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4856 </a><a href="#h122-0-226" id="h122-0-226" class="i">+&lt;h2 id=&quot;more-plugins&quot; tabindex=&quot;-1&quot;&gt;More plugins &lt;a class=&quot;header-anchor&quot; href=&quot;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/my-nvim-config-2022/#more-plugins&quot;&gt;&lt;span aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;header-anchor__symbol&quot;&gt;#&lt;/span&gt;
   4857 </a><a href="#h122-0-227" id="h122-0-227" class="i">+      &lt;span class=&quot;screen-reader-only&quot;&gt;Direct link to this section&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
   4858 </a><a href="#h122-0-228" id="h122-0-228" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Those are my most &amp;quot;showy&amp;quot; plugins. I use a lot more but are just for tiny things like color colorizer, lsp config, color-schemes, etc.
   4859 </a><a href="#h122-0-229" id="h122-0-229" class="i">+I strongly suggest that you vim config should be minimal as you can to get a faster start and use Lua instead of vimrc. This will make your
   4860 </a><a href="#h122-0-230" id="h122-0-230" class="i">+life easier and happier.&lt;/p&gt;
   4861 </a><a href="#h122-0-231" id="h122-0-231" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;If you wanna see all my nvim config you can check my repo
   4862 </a><a href="#h122-0-232" id="h122-0-232" class="i">+&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/hectoraldairah/nvim-config&quot;&gt;nvim configuration&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4863 </a><a href="#h122-0-233" id="h122-0-233" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It&#39;s not that fancy so maybe you can understand everything there.&lt;/p&gt;
   4864 </a><a href="#h122-0-234" id="h122-0-234" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Well, that it! I know for sure that this plugins list will be changing over time but I will stay with the philosphy of less is more&lt;/p&gt;
   4865 </a><a href="#h122-0-235" id="h122-0-235" class="i">+ ]]&gt;

   4871 </a><a href="#h122-0-241" id="h122-0-241" class="i">+    &lt;updated&gt;2021-12-31T00:00:00Z&lt;/updated&gt;
   4872 </a><a href="#h122-0-242" id="h122-0-242" class="i">+    &lt;id&gt;https://bitbyte.blog/blog/things-i-want-to-learn-on-2022/&lt;/id&gt;
   4873 </a><a href="#h122-0-243" id="h122-0-243" class="i">+    &lt;content type=&quot;html&quot;&gt;
   4874 </a><a href="#h122-0-244" id="h122-0-244" class="i">+      &lt;![CDATA[ &lt;p&gt;It&#39;s the end of the year, and I&#39;m starting to think about what I want to learn in 2022.&lt;/p&gt;
   4875 </a><a href="#h122-0-245" id="h122-0-245" class="i">+&lt;ol&gt;
   4876 </a><a href="#h122-0-246" id="h122-0-246" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4877 </a><a href="#h122-0-247" id="h122-0-247" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A new programming language: I&#39;m thinking on Clojure, Elm, or Elixir. I need to understand better the concepts of functional programming and how to use them. Maybe I&#39;ll use this expertise to apply javascript.&lt;/p&gt;
   4878 </a><a href="#h122-0-248" id="h122-0-248" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4879 </a><a href="#h122-0-249" id="h122-0-249" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4880 </a><a href="#h122-0-250" id="h122-0-250" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;A new pixel art tool: I used to work with Photoshop and Adobe Flash to make pixel art animations, but I don&#39;t want to use them anymore (I can&#39;t run any Adobe App now) so I&#39;m thinking to use &lt;a href=&quot;https://aseprite.org/&quot;&gt;aseprite&lt;/a&gt; because I did some basic animation with it two years ago.&lt;/p&gt;
   4881 </a><a href="#h122-0-251" id="h122-0-251" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4882 </a><a href="#h122-0-252" id="h122-0-252" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4883 </a><a href="#h122-0-253" id="h122-0-253" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Blender: I did some 3D animations when I was like 16? on an old mini laptop that I had. It was good at the time with only 2 Gb of ram but man, the software is getting ram expensive. Maybe I can start to make some things with my new computer.&lt;/p&gt;
   4884 </a><a href="#h122-0-254" id="h122-0-254" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4885 </a><a href="#h122-0-255" id="h122-0-255" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4886 </a><a href="#h122-0-256" id="h122-0-256" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;How to talk in public: Since 2019, I get the interest to do talks about tech with one cup of acid humor on it. The pandemic was a big problem here because there are no more live meetups and I just forget about it. With the online meetups, I can feel a chance to do it.&lt;/p&gt;
   4887 </a><a href="#h122-0-257" id="h122-0-257" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4888 </a><a href="#h122-0-258" id="h122-0-258" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4889 </a><a href="#h122-0-259" id="h122-0-259" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Back-end: Well, maybe this is kind of huge for me. I&#39;ve been doing front-end stuff for a while and my backend skills are getting pretty bad. My experience working with &lt;a href=&quot;https://expressjs.com/es/&quot;&gt;Express&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://adonisjs.com/&quot;&gt;Adonis&lt;/a&gt; was pretty good, but it was simple things. I don&#39;t know anything about databases too. So, yeah. Maybe I&#39;ll buy a course from &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.udemy.com/&quot;&gt;Udemy&lt;/a&gt; for it.&lt;/p&gt;
   4890 </a><a href="#h122-0-260" id="h122-0-260" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4891 </a><a href="#h122-0-261" id="h122-0-261" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4892 </a><a href="#h122-0-262" id="h122-0-262" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;CSS Art: Yes, another art stuff. All the &lt;a href=&quot;https://codepen.io/tag/css-art&quot;&gt;beautiful CSS art that is on codepen&lt;/a&gt; makes me want to do something similar. I&#39;m not sure what exactly but some 3D CSS animations are on my eye.&lt;/p&gt;
   4893 </a><a href="#h122-0-263" id="h122-0-263" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4894 </a><a href="#h122-0-264" id="h122-0-264" class="i">+&lt;li&gt;
   4895 </a><a href="#h122-0-265" id="h122-0-265" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Being fluent in Esperanto and learning more about romantic languages: Duolingo and &lt;a href=&quot;https://lernu.net/&quot;&gt;Lernu&lt;/a&gt; are my best friends here.&lt;/p&gt;
   4896 </a><a href="#h122-0-266" id="h122-0-266" class="i">+&lt;/li&gt;
   4897 </a><a href="#h122-0-267" id="h122-0-267" class="i">+&lt;/ol&gt;
   4898 </a><a href="#h122-0-268" id="h122-0-268" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;That&#39;s it. I don&#39;t want to write more on this post to avoid feeling bad at the end of 2022.&lt;/p&gt;
   4899 </a><a href="#h122-0-269" id="h122-0-269" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Happy 2022!&lt;/p&gt;

   4909 </a><a href="#h122-0-279" id="h122-0-279" class="i">+      &lt;![CDATA[ &lt;p&gt;Hello, world! This is my first post ever made on this new site.&lt;/p&gt;
   4910 </a><a href="#h122-0-280" id="h122-0-280" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is the place where I&#39;m going to write about my life, my work, and my hobbies. The things that I want to save in a secure place instead of my head.&lt;/p&gt;
   4911 </a><a href="#h122-0-281" id="h122-0-281" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Why am I making this website and not using some other tool like medium?
   4912 </a><a href="#h122-0-282" id="h122-0-282" class="i">+Well, the first reason is... I don&#39;t know how to make a website so I&#39;m making this one.&lt;/p&gt;
   4913 </a><a href="#h122-0-283" id="h122-0-283" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The second reason is that I want control over the content of my posts and something very simple.
   4914 </a><a href="#h122-0-284" id="h122-0-284" class="i">+I don&#39;t want paywalls, ads, etc. It&#39;s just a blog, not a new NTF collection.&lt;/p&gt;
   4915 </a><a href="#h122-0-285" id="h122-0-285" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Well, maybe I&#39;ll add some ads in the future. &lt;strong&gt;That&#39;s a bad joke&lt;/strong&gt; please ignore it.&lt;/p&gt;
   4916 </a><a href="#h122-0-286" id="h122-0-286" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;The next post will be about how I&#39;m making this website and the resources I&#39;m using.&lt;/p&gt;
   4917 </a><a href="#h122-0-287" id="h122-0-287" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;But if you&#39;re a little impatient, you can check out this &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/hectoraldairah/bitbyte-blog&quot;&gt;Github repo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
   4918 </a><a href="#h122-0-288" id="h122-0-288" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I&#39;m using &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.11ty.dev/&quot;&gt;Eleventy&lt;/a&gt; btw.&lt;/p&gt;
   4919 </a><a href="#h122-0-289" id="h122-0-289" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Quote of the day:
   4920 </a><a href="#h122-0-290" id="h122-0-290" class="i">+You need to finish your shit before you start your next one. - IDK&lt;/p&gt;
   4921 </a><a href="#h122-0-291" id="h122-0-291" class="i">+ ]]&gt;

  12046 </a><a href="#h141-0-1" id="h141-0-1" class="i">+title: &#39;Ghost Love&#39;
  12047 </a><a href="#h141-0-2" id="h141-0-2" class="i">+date: 2021-12-08
  12048 </a><a href="#h141-0-3" id="h141-0-3" class="i">+tags: [&#39;PixelArt&#39;]
  12049 </a><a href="#h141-0-4" id="h141-0-4" class="i">+description: &#39;A spooky friend&#39;
  12050 </a><a href="#h141-0-5" id="h141-0-5" class="i">+image: ghost-love.png
  12051 </a><a href="#h141-0-6" id="h141-0-6" class="i">+dir: ghost-love
  12052 </a><a href="#h141-0-7" id="h141-0-7" class="i">+---
  12053 </a><a href="#h141-0-8" id="h141-0-8" class="i">+
  12054 </a><a href="#h141-0-9" id="h141-0-9" class="i">+Pixelart is my favorite style for videogames. Why?
  12055 </a><a href="#h141-0-10" id="h141-0-10" class="i">+
  12056 </a><a href="#h141-0-11" id="h141-0-11" class="i">+When I was a child, I had only three videogame consoles; the ps1, ps2 and the GBA.
  12057 </a><a href="#h141-0-12" id="h141-0-12" class="i">+
  12058 </a><a href="#h141-0-13" id="h141-0-13" class="i">+I missed a lot of &quot;new&quot; games until I got a PC and I started to play more &quot;new&quot; games.
  12059 </a><a href="#h141-0-14" id="h141-0-14" class="i">+Even then, the PC was an old mini-laptop with only 2 GB of RAM.
  12060 </a><a href="#h141-0-15" id="h141-0-15" class="i">+
  12061 </a><a href="#h141-0-16" id="h141-0-16" class="i">+That&#39;s the reason I used to play emulators for the SNES, Gameboy and GBA and I fall in
  12062 </a><a href="#h141-0-17" id="h141-0-17" class="i">+love with the retro style.
  12063 </a><a href="#h141-0-18" id="h141-0-18" class="i">+
  12064 </a><a href="#h141-0-19" id="h141-0-19" class="i">+As you can see on this website, I like the pixelart style. So, why not start to making it?
  12065 </a><a href="#h141-0-20" id="h141-0-20" class="i">+
  12066 </a><a href="#h141-0-21" id="h141-0-21" class="i">+I always think I&#39;m not an **artsy boy**. I have zero art skills... I don&#39;t like that.
  12067 </a><a href="#h141-0-22" id="h141-0-22" class="i">+
  12068 </a><a href="#h141-0-23" id="h141-0-23" class="i">+That&#39;s why I started with pixelart. The _i love the retro style_ + _i wanna make some art that doesn&#39;t suck_
  12069 </a><a href="#h141-0-24" id="h141-0-24" class="i">+
  12070 </a><a href="#h141-0-25" id="h141-0-25" class="i">+That boring introduction was for this little guy.
  12071 </a><a href="#h141-0-26" id="h141-0-26" class="i">+
  12072 </a><a href="#h141-0-27" id="h141-0-27" class="i">+My first pixel art ever made.
  12073 </a><a href="#h141-0-28" id="h141-0-28" class="i">+
  12074 </a><a href="#h141-0-29" id="h141-0-29" class="i">+![Spooky Ghost](ghost-love.png)
  12075 </a><a href="#h141-0-30" id="h141-0-30" class="i">+
  12076 </a><a href="#h141-0-31" id="h141-0-31" class="i">+This was made with [Asperite](https://www.aseprite.org/) and just a little bit of time.
  12077 </a><a href="#h141-0-32" id="h141-0-32" class="i">+
  12078 </a><a href="#h141-0-33" id="h141-0-33" class="i">+It was made on the fly, and the color palette I chose was random.
  12079 </a><a href="#h141-0-34" id="h141-0-34" class="i">+
  12080 </a><a href="#h141-0-35" id="h141-0-35" class="i">+I don&#39;t remember the canvas size.
  12081 </a><a href="#h141-0-36" id="h141-0-36" class="i">+
  12082 </a><a href="#h141-0-37" id="h141-0-37" class="i">+Ghost Love makes me happy because it&#39;s a reminder that I can make art.
  12083 </a><b>diff --git a/<a id="h142" href="../file/dist/pixelart/ghost-love/ghost-love.png.html">dist/pixelart/ghost-love/ghost-love.png</a> b/<a href="../file/dist/pixelart/ghost-love/ghost-love.png.html">dist/pixelart/ghost-love/ghost-love.png</a></b>

  12210 </a><a href="#h143-0-123" id="h143-0-123" class="i">+  &lt;h3&gt;Ghost Love&lt;/h3&gt;
  12211 </a><a href="#h143-0-124" id="h143-0-124" class="i">+  
  12212 </a><a href="#h143-0-125" id="h143-0-125" class="i">+   &lt;h4&gt;A spooky friend  ::  &lt;time style=&quot;font-size: 14px&quot; datetime=&quot;Dec 7, 2021&quot;&gt;Dec 7, 2021&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;  
  12213 </a><a href="#h143-0-126" id="h143-0-126" class="i">+  &lt;/div&gt;
  12214 </a><a href="#h143-0-127" id="h143-0-127" class="i">+
  12215 </a><a href="#h143-0-128" id="h143-0-128" class="i">+
  12216 </a><a href="#h143-0-129" id="h143-0-129" class="i">+
  12217 </a><a href="#h143-0-130" id="h143-0-130" class="i">+&lt;ul class=&quot;[ tag-list ]&quot; aria-describedby=&quot;tags-desc&quot;&gt;
  12218 </a><a href="#h143-0-131" id="h143-0-131" class="i">+  
  12219 </a><a href="#h143-0-132" id="h143-0-132" class="i">+  &lt;li&gt;
  12220 </a><a href="#h143-0-133" id="h143-0-133" class="i">+    &lt;a href=&quot;/tag/pixelart/&quot;&gt;#Pixelart&lt;/a&gt;
  12221 </a><a href="#h143-0-134" id="h143-0-134" class="i">+  &lt;/li&gt;
  12222 </a><a href="#h143-0-135" id="h143-0-135" class="i">+  
  12223 </a><a href="#h143-0-136" id="h143-0-136" class="i">+&lt;/ul&gt;
  12224 </a><a href="#h143-0-137" id="h143-0-137" class="i">+
  12225 </a><a href="#h143-0-138" id="h143-0-138" class="i">+&lt;/div&gt;
  12226 </a><a href="#h143-0-139" id="h143-0-139" class="i">+
  12227 </a><a href="#h143-0-140" id="h143-0-140" class="i">+        &lt;main tabindex=&quot;-1&quot; id=&quot;main-content&quot; class=&quot;[ main-content ]&quot;&gt;
  12228 </a><a href="#h143-0-141" id="h143-0-141" class="i">+            &lt;section class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;
  12229 </a><a href="#h143-0-142" id="h143-0-142" class="i">+            
  12230 </a><a href="#h143-0-143" id="h143-0-143" class="i">+  &lt;article class=&quot;constrained&quot;&gt;
  12231 </a><a href="#h143-0-144" id="h143-0-144" class="i">+    &lt;div class=&quot;[ page-content ]&quot;&gt;
  12232 </a><a href="#h143-0-145" id="h143-0-145" class="i">+        &lt;p&gt;Pixelart is my favorite style for videogames. Why?&lt;/p&gt;
  12233 </a><a href="#h143-0-146" id="h143-0-146" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;When I was a child, I had only three videogame consoles; the ps1, ps2 and the GBA.&lt;/p&gt;
  12234 </a><a href="#h143-0-147" id="h143-0-147" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I missed a lot of &amp;quot;new&amp;quot; games until I got a PC and I started to play more &amp;quot;new&amp;quot; games.
  12235 </a><a href="#h143-0-148" id="h143-0-148" class="i">+Even then, the PC was an old mini-laptop with only 2 GB of RAM.&lt;/p&gt;
  12236 </a><a href="#h143-0-149" id="h143-0-149" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;That&#39;s the reason I used to play emulators for the SNES, Gameboy and GBA and I fall in
  12237 </a><a href="#h143-0-150" id="h143-0-150" class="i">+love with the retro style.&lt;/p&gt;
  12238 </a><a href="#h143-0-151" id="h143-0-151" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;As you can see on this website, I like the pixelart style. So, why not start to making it?&lt;/p&gt;
  12239 </a><a href="#h143-0-152" id="h143-0-152" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I always think I&#39;m not an &lt;strong&gt;artsy boy&lt;/strong&gt;. I have zero art skills... I don&#39;t like that.&lt;/p&gt;
  12240 </a><a href="#h143-0-153" id="h143-0-153" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;That&#39;s why I started with pixelart. The &lt;em&gt;i love the retro style&lt;/em&gt; + &lt;em&gt;i wanna make some art that doesn&#39;t suck&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  12241 </a><a href="#h143-0-154" id="h143-0-154" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;That boring introduction was for this little guy.&lt;/p&gt;
  12242 </a><a href="#h143-0-155" id="h143-0-155" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;My first pixel art ever made.&lt;/p&gt;
  12243 </a><a href="#h143-0-156" id="h143-0-156" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;ghost-love.png&quot; alt=&quot;Spooky Ghost&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  12244 </a><a href="#h143-0-157" id="h143-0-157" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This was made with &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.aseprite.org/&quot;&gt;Asperite&lt;/a&gt; and just a little bit of time.&lt;/p&gt;
  12245 </a><a href="#h143-0-158" id="h143-0-158" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;It was made on the fly, and the color palette I chose was random.&lt;/p&gt;
  12246 </a><a href="#h143-0-159" id="h143-0-159" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I don&#39;t remember the canvas size.&lt;/p&gt;
  12247 </a><a href="#h143-0-160" id="h143-0-160" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;Ghost Love makes me happy because it&#39;s a reminder that I can make art.&lt;/p&gt;
  12248 </a><a href="#h143-0-161" id="h143-0-161" class="i">+
  12249 </a><a href="#h143-0-162" id="h143-0-162" class="i">+    &lt;/div&gt;

  12695 </a><a href="#h147-0-145" id="h147-0-145" class="i">+        &lt;p&gt;So, in order to get better at making pixel art I started to get into tutorials for learning.&lt;/p&gt;
  12696 </a><a href="#h147-0-146" id="h147-0-146" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;For now, my first learning source was Youtube. I started to watch a lot of pixelart art channels for begginer tips and tricks to start making my first compositions.&lt;/p&gt;
  12697 </a><a href="#h147-0-147" id="h147-0-147" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;One thing I learned is not to start making big pixelarts canvas, instead you can start with a 8x8 canvas. It&#39;s more easier to create very little drawings and you have more control about space and colors.&lt;/p&gt;
  12698 </a><a href="#h147-0-148" id="h147-0-148" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;This is my first composition, its like a Mario&#39;s Ghost but witk a pink ink. This drawing has very little variations (same color but different shades) to start making shadows and lights.&lt;/p&gt;
  12699 </a><a href="#h147-0-149" id="h147-0-149" class="i">+&lt;p&gt;I think it&#39;s pretty good just for my first (real) attemp.&lt;/p&gt;

  12983 </a><a href="#h151-0-7" id="h151-0-7" class="i">+
  12984 </a><a href="#h151-0-8" id="h151-0-8" class="i">+Hello, world! This is my first post ever made on this new site.
  12985 </a><a href="#h151-0-9" id="h151-0-9" class="i">+
  12986 </a><a href="#h151-0-10" id="h151-0-10" class="i">+This is the place where I&#39;m going to write about my life, my work, and my hobbies. The things that I want to save in a secure place instead of my head.
  12987 </a><a href="#h151-0-11" id="h151-0-11" class="i">+
  12988 </a><a href="#h151-0-12" id="h151-0-12" class="i">+Why am I making this website and not using some other tool like medium?
  12989 </a><a href="#h151-0-13" id="h151-0-13" class="i">+Well, the first reason is... I don&#39;t know how to make a website so I&#39;m making this one.
  12990 </a><a href="#h151-0-14" id="h151-0-14" class="i">+
  12991 </a><a href="#h151-0-15" id="h151-0-15" class="i">+The second reason is that I want control over the content of my posts and something very simple.
  12992 </a><a href="#h151-0-16" id="h151-0-16" class="i">+I don&#39;t want paywalls, ads, etc. It&#39;s just a blog, not a new NTF collection.
  12993 </a><a href="#h151-0-17" id="h151-0-17" class="i">+
  12994 </a><a href="#h151-0-18" id="h151-0-18" class="i">+Well, maybe I&#39;ll add some ads in the future. **That&#39;s a bad joke** please ignore it.
  12995 </a><a href="#h151-0-19" id="h151-0-19" class="i">+
  12996 </a><a href="#h151-0-20" id="h151-0-20" class="i">+The next post will be about how I&#39;m making this website and the resources I&#39;m using.
  12997 </a><a href="#h151-0-21" id="h151-0-21" class="i">+
  12998 </a><a href="#h151-0-22" id="h151-0-22" class="i">+But if you&#39;re a little impatient, you can check out this [Github repo](https://github.com/hectoraldairah/bitbyte-blog)
  12999 </a><a href="#h151-0-23" id="h151-0-23" class="i">+
  13000 </a><a href="#h151-0-24" id="h151-0-24" class="i">+I&#39;m using [Eleventy](https://www.11ty.dev/) btw.
  13001 </a><a href="#h151-0-25" id="h151-0-25" class="i">+
  13002 </a><a href="#h151-0-26" id="h151-0-26" class="i">+Quote of the day:
