  13013 </a><a href="#h152-0-7" id="h152-0-7" class="i">+date: 2024-01-07
  13014 </a><a href="#h152-0-8" id="h152-0-8" class="i">+tags: [&#39;Go&#39;]
  13015 </a><a href="#h152-0-9" id="h152-0-9" class="i">+---
  13016 </a><a href="#h152-0-10" id="h152-0-10" class="i">+# Why Go?
  13017 </a><a href="#h152-0-11" id="h152-0-11" class="i">+
  13018 </a><a href="#h152-0-12" id="h152-0-12" class="i">+As I mentioned before here on my blog, one of my goals of new years eve is to learn more about back-end development  to [[Be a better Front-End Dev]].  
  13019 </a><a href="#h152-0-13" id="h152-0-13" class="i">+
  13020 </a><a href="#h152-0-14" id="h152-0-14" class="i">+At my job, I already tried some back-end stuff with some languages:
  13021 </a><a href="#h152-0-15" id="h152-0-15" class="i">+1. Node.js aka Javascript
  13022 </a><a href="#h152-0-16" id="h152-0-16" class="i">+2. Python
  13023 </a><a href="#h152-0-17" id="h152-0-17" class="i">+3. Java... ewww
  13024 </a><a href="#h152-0-18" id="h152-0-18" class="i">+
  13025 </a><a href="#h152-0-19" id="h152-0-19" class="i">+The first path that I take was using Node.js, the decision was very easy to me. I already knew [[Javascript]], so touching some  AWS Lambdas and Micro-Services at my Job wasn&#39;t every hard to follow and to commit something to production. 
  13026 </a><a href="#h152-0-20" id="h152-0-20" class="i">+
  13027 </a><a href="#h152-0-21" id="h152-0-21" class="i">+It is fine (I guess) but I wanted to learn other thing more that Javascript to expand my horizons. 
  13028 </a><a href="#h152-0-22" id="h152-0-22" class="i">+
  13029 </a><a href="#h152-0-23" id="h152-0-23" class="i">+Later on, I started to work with Python, that is not completely new for me. In some point of my early dev career, I tried Flask to develop a simple REST API. It was very fun but not so much appealing for me to keep me in that way of back-end development.
  13030 </a><a href="#h152-0-24" id="h152-0-24" class="i">+
  13031 </a><a href="#h152-0-25" id="h152-0-25" class="i">+Thank god that the projects that I&#39;ve been working at my job are very well designed and with good project structure. Even the test are very simple straightforward to follow. Committing a new feature for production? GG izi.
  13032 </a><a href="#h152-0-26" id="h152-0-26" class="i">+
  13033 </a><a href="#h152-0-27" id="h152-0-27" class="i">+Python is fun, I enjoyed PyTest so much, even more than some unit test tools in Javascript, but at the end of the day I think that I need to learn some __REAL__ back-end language. 
  13034 </a><a href="#h152-0-28" id="h152-0-28" class="i">+
  13035 </a><a href="#h152-0-29" id="h152-0-29" class="i">+&gt; The &quot;REAL&quot; word that I use before it refers better to &quot;learn a compiled language&quot; or some &quot;blazingly fast language&quot;. Don&#39;t be so judgy, please.
  13036 </a><a href="#h152-0-30" id="h152-0-30" class="i">+
  13037 </a><a href="#h152-0-31" id="h152-0-31" class="i">+So Go was on my eye for a while. I watched a lot of videos about on Youtube and gives me a lot of good  impressions:
  13038 </a><a href="#h152-0-32" id="h152-0-32" class="i">+1. The syntax is very well designed and elegant
  13039 </a><a href="#h152-0-33" id="h152-0-33" class="i">+2. It is  compiled language (blazingly fast)
  13040 </a><a href="#h152-0-34" id="h152-0-34" class="i">+3. Strongly type
  13041 </a><a href="#h152-0-35" id="h152-0-35" class="i">+4. Good documentation
  13042 </a><a href="#h152-0-36" id="h152-0-36" class="i">+5. High employability 
  13043 </a><a href="#h152-0-37" id="h152-0-37" class="i">+6. Fun
  13044 </a><a href="#h152-0-38" id="h152-0-38" class="i">+### Why not Java?
  13045 </a><a href="#h152-0-39" id="h152-0-39" class="i">+Ewww.
  13046 </a><a href="#h152-0-40" id="h152-0-40" class="i">+
  13047 </a><a href="#h152-0-41" id="h152-0-41" class="i">+### How I started? 
  13048 </a><a href="#h152-0-42" id="h152-0-42" class="i">+
  13049 </a><a href="#h152-0-43" id="h152-0-43" class="i">+I highly recommend to check to [official documentation](https://go.dev/doc/effective_go) first. It&#39;s every well written, almost well enough as the Elixir documentation _chef kiss emoji_. 
  13050 </a><a href="#h152-0-44" id="h152-0-44" class="i">+
  13051 </a><a href="#h152-0-45" id="h152-0-45" class="i">+Next, you can GO (get it? hahaha :c ) to this next resources:
  13052 </a><a href="#h152-0-46" id="h152-0-46" class="i">+1. [Go in Exercism](https://exercism.org/tracks/go): This is my first option when I need to learn some new programming language
  13053 </a><a href="#h152-0-47" id="h152-0-47" class="i">+2. [Boot.dev Go Course](https://www.boot.dev/tracks/backend): Very fun and easy to follow
  13054 </a><a href="#h152-0-48" id="h152-0-48" class="i">+3. [100 Go Mistakes and How to Avoid Them](https://100go.co/): This is fucking great and very useful when you want to make the things right.
  13055 </a><a href="#h152-0-49" id="h152-0-49" class="i">+4. [Gophercises](https://gophercises.com/) : Imagine a gym but for learning Go, that&#39;s right.
  13056 </a><a href="#h152-0-50" id="h152-0-50" class="i">+
  13057 </a><a href="#h152-0-51" id="h152-0-51" class="i">+Later on I started to building something for and by myself. I&#39;m working in a very simple CLI program to publish my Obsidian notes here on the blog and a Pokemon project... shhh is secret for now.
  13058 </a><a href="#h152-0-52" id="h152-0-52" class="i">+
  13059 </a><a href="#h152-0-53" id="h152-0-53" class="i">+### Do you expect something more?
  13060 </a><a href="#h152-0-54" id="h152-0-54" class="i">+
  13061 </a><a href="#h152-0-55" id="h152-0-55" class="i">+I&#39;m very new to Go so I can&#39;t offer new ways for learning it, what I can offer you is a very well respected Youtube channels to continue with your journey
  13062 </a><a href="#h152-0-56" id="h152-0-56" class="i">+
  13063 </a><a href="#h152-0-57" id="h152-0-57" class="i">+1. [Bashbunni](https://www.youtube.com/@bashbunni)
  13064 </a><a href="#h152-0-58" id="h152-0-58" class="i">+2. [Anthony GG](https://www.youtube.com/@anthonygg_)
  13065 </a><a href="#h152-0-59" id="h152-0-59" class="i">+3. [Go Simplified](https://www.youtube.com/@GoSimplifiedChannel)
  13066 </a><a href="#h152-0-60" id="h152-0-60" class="i">+4. [Should you learn Go in 2023?](https://www.youtube.com/@dreamsofcode)
  13067 </a><a href="#h152-0-61" id="h152-0-61" class="i">+
  13068 </a><a href="#h152-0-62" id="h152-0-62" class="i">+Good luck!
  13069 </a><b>diff --git a/<a id="h153" href="../file/dist/posts/low-tech_websites_and_why_you_should_have_one_%28maybe%29.md.html">dist/posts/low-tech_websites_and_why_you_should_have_one_(maybe).md</a> b/<a href="../file/dist/posts/low-tech_websites_and_why_you_should_have_one_%28maybe%29.md.html">dist/posts/low-tech_websites_and_why_you_should_have_one_(maybe).md</a></b>

  13080 </a><a href="#h153-0-9" id="h153-0-9" class="i">+# Getting into low-tech
  13081 </a><a href="#h153-0-10" id="h153-0-10" class="i">+
  13082 </a><a href="#h153-0-11" id="h153-0-11" class="i">+If you&#39;re very curious you already knew that I like to make some **pixel art** in my free time (It&#39;s a very noble hobby btw) and learning new techniques for making my sprites less akward.
  13083 </a><a href="#h153-0-12" id="h153-0-12" class="i">+
  13084 </a><a href="#h153-0-13" id="h153-0-13" class="i">+In one of
  13085 </a><a href="#h153-0-14" id="h153-0-14" class="i">+
  13086 </a><a href="#h153-0-15" id="h153-0-15" class="i">+Some have a beautifull desing, very cool animations, videos in the background or some kind of big interactive feature that makes the site stand-up.
  13087 </a><a href="#h153-0-16" id="h153-0-16" class="i">+
  13088 </a><a href="#h153-0-17" id="h153-0-17" class="i">+## What is low-tech?

  13091 </a><b>diff --git a/<a id="h154" href="../file/dist/posts/my_nvim_config_2022.md.html">dist/posts/my_nvim_config_2022.md</a> b/<a href="../file/dist/posts/my_nvim_config_2022.md.html">dist/posts/my_nvim_config_2022.md</a></b>

  13093 </a><a href="#h154-0-0" id="h154-0-0" class="i">+---
  13094 </a><a href="#h154-0-1" id="h154-0-1" class="i">+title: My nvim config 2022
  13095 </a><a href="#h154-0-2" id="h154-0-2" class="i">+date: 2022-08-06
  13096 </a><a href="#h154-0-3" id="h154-0-3" class="i">+description: A collection of plugins that I use for nvim
  13097 </a><a href="#h154-0-4" id="h154-0-4" class="i">+featured: true
  13098 </a><a href="#h154-0-5" id="h154-0-5" class="i">+tags: [&#39;nvim&#39;, &#39;tools&#39;, &#39;programming&#39;]
  13099 </a><a href="#h154-0-6" id="h154-0-6" class="i">+---
  13100 </a><a href="#h154-0-7" id="h154-0-7" class="i">+
  13101 </a><a href="#h154-0-8" id="h154-0-8" class="i">+I&#39;ve been using the vim/nvim ecosystem for more than a year and I just love it.
  13102 </a><a href="#h154-0-9" id="h154-0-9" class="i">+Using NVIM improved my workflow so much after I learned the basics of it and how to properly create a base configuration.
  13103 </a><a href="#h154-0-10" id="h154-0-10" class="i">+
  13104 </a><a href="#h154-0-11" id="h154-0-11" class="i">+It&#39;s not so much hard to use despite the **insanely amount** of memes on Twitter. Please, stop with the exit vim joke is not funny anymore.
  13105 </a><a href="#h154-0-12" id="h154-0-12" class="i">+&lt;br&gt;
  13106 </a><a href="#h154-0-13" id="h154-0-13" class="i">+I&#39;ll write a post about some programming jokes that aged like milk.
  13107 </a><a href="#h154-0-14" id="h154-0-14" class="i">+
  13108 </a><a href="#h154-0-15" id="h154-0-15" class="i">+## Lua is love 
  13109 </a><a href="#h154-0-16" id="h154-0-16" class="i">+
  13110 </a><a href="#h154-0-17" id="h154-0-17" class="i">+VIM comes with a config file, typically the .vimrc that is written in vimscript.
  13111 </a><a href="#h154-0-18" id="h154-0-18" class="i">+Even though, is not that bad. I find it difficult to manually configure and the .vimrc file becomes so big if you add a lot of plugins to try.
  13112 </a><a href="#h154-0-19" id="h154-0-19" class="i">+
  13113 </a><a href="#h154-0-20" id="h154-0-20" class="i">+NVIM uses Lua as an alternative to configuring nvim. It&#39;s a very easy programming language, you can learn the basics in a week and start using it with that, you can create a more organized structure to save your plugins and config files.
  13114 </a><a href="#h154-0-21" id="h154-0-21" class="i">+Another advantage to using Lua is the community around it.
  13115 </a><a href="#h154-0-22" id="h154-0-22" class="i">+
  13116 </a><a href="#h154-0-23" id="h154-0-23" class="i">+A lot of new plugins for nvim are written on Lua, making it faster than other languages like JavaScript.
  13117 </a><a href="#h154-0-24" id="h154-0-24" class="i">+
  13118 </a><a href="#h154-0-25" id="h154-0-25" class="i">+Also, making my NVIM config modular helps **a lot** with the organization of everything.
  13119 </a><a href="#h154-0-26" id="h154-0-26" class="i">+
  13120 </a><a href="#h154-0-27" id="h154-0-27" class="i">+Next, I&#39;m gonna tell you what plugins I use the most.
  13121 </a><a href="#h154-0-28" id="h154-0-28" class="i">+
  13122 </a><a href="#h154-0-29" id="h154-0-29" class="i">+## Most Have Plugins
  13123 </a><a href="#h154-0-30" id="h154-0-30" class="i">+
  13124 </a><a href="#h154-0-31" id="h154-0-31" class="i">+This plugins are a must if you wanna improve you NVIM experience.
  13125 </a><a href="#h154-0-32" id="h154-0-32" class="i">+
  13126 </a><a href="#h154-0-33" id="h154-0-33" class="i">+### Telescope
  13127 </a><a href="#h154-0-34" id="h154-0-34" class="i">+
  13128 </a><a href="#h154-0-35" id="h154-0-35" class="i">+This is one of the plugins I use the most, one of the best fuzzy finders around here.
  13129 </a><a href="#h154-0-36" id="h154-0-36" class="i">+
  13130 </a><a href="#h154-0-37" id="h154-0-37" class="i">+I like how fast it is and a lot of the options that you can configure with it. Search by file or by a regex expression with a nice UI and a lot of color-schemes are supported.
  13131 </a><a href="#h154-0-38" id="h154-0-38" class="i">+
  13132 </a><a href="#h154-0-39" id="h154-0-39" class="i">+![telescope](../../assets/images/tele.gif)
  13133 </a><a href="#h154-0-40" id="h154-0-40" class="i">+
  13134 </a><a href="#h154-0-41" id="h154-0-41" class="i">+Try it: [Telescope plugin](https://github.com/nvim-telescope/telescope.nvim)
  13135 </a><a href="#h154-0-42" id="h154-0-42" class="i">+
  13136 </a><a href="#h154-0-43" id="h154-0-43" class="i">+### nvim-tree
  13137 </a><a href="#h154-0-44" id="h154-0-44" class="i">+
  13138 </a><a href="#h154-0-45" id="h154-0-45" class="i">+I see it as the [NERDTree](https://github.com/preservim/nerdtree) improved, very light and blazingly fast.
  13139 </a><a href="#h154-0-46" id="h154-0-46" class="i">+You can use web-dev-icons. Extremely configurable but no overwhelming.
  13140 </a><a href="#h154-0-47" id="h154-0-47" class="i">+
  13141 </a><a href="#h154-0-48" id="h154-0-48" class="i">+It&#39;s easy to learn all the keybindings, wanna add a new file? Just type a, edit? e, open? o. So simple and intuitive
  13142 </a><a href="#h154-0-49" id="h154-0-49" class="i">+
  13143 </a><a href="#h154-0-50" id="h154-0-50" class="i">+![telescope](../../assets/images/nvimtree.gif)
  13144 </a><a href="#h154-0-51" id="h154-0-51" class="i">+
  13145 </a><a href="#h154-0-52" id="h154-0-52" class="i">+Try it: [nvim-tree plugin](https://github.com/kyazdani42/nvim-tree.lua)
  13146 </a><a href="#h154-0-53" id="h154-0-53" class="i">+
  13147 </a><a href="#h154-0-54" id="h154-0-54" class="i">+### nvim-tree-sitter
  13148 </a><a href="#h154-0-55" id="h154-0-55" class="i">+
  13149 </a><a href="#h154-0-56" id="h154-0-56" class="i">+Tree sitter it&#39;s a parser generator for our code in order to nvim can understand our code.
  13150 </a><a href="#h154-0-57" id="h154-0-57" class="i">+This is very helpful because you can have a lot of cool features for your favorite programming language, like: syntax highlight, folding, text-object manipulation, etc.
  13151 </a><a href="#h154-0-58" id="h154-0-58" class="i">+
  13152 </a><a href="#h154-0-59" id="h154-0-59" class="i">+The list of supported languages is huge and a lot of new features are being added to nvim.
  13153 </a><a href="#h154-0-60" id="h154-0-60" class="i">+
  13154 </a><a href="#h154-0-61" id="h154-0-61" class="i">+Try it: [nvim-tree-sitter plugin](https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter)
  13155 </a><a href="#h154-0-62" id="h154-0-62" class="i">+
  13156 </a><a href="#h154-0-63" id="h154-0-63" class="i">+### Float Term
  13157 </a><a href="#h154-0-64" id="h154-0-64" class="i">+
  13158 </a><a href="#h154-0-65" id="h154-0-65" class="i">+This is one has increased my productivity a lot. Instead of open a new terminal somewhere else of changing between spaces
  13159 </a><a href="#h154-0-66" id="h154-0-66" class="i">+I just open a new float term. Float term is just a terminal but... floating in your nvim space.
  13160 </a><a href="#h154-0-67" id="h154-0-67" class="i">+
  13161 </a><a href="#h154-0-68" id="h154-0-68" class="i">+You can have a lot of float terms opened but one is just enough for me. The easy access is hot.
  13162 </a><a href="#h154-0-69" id="h154-0-69" class="i">+
  13163 </a><a href="#h154-0-70" id="h154-0-70" class="i">+![Float Term](../../assets/images/floatterm.gif)
  13164 </a><a href="#h154-0-71" id="h154-0-71" class="i">+
  13165 </a><a href="#h154-0-72" id="h154-0-72" class="i">+Try it: [Float Term plugin](https://github.com/voldikss/vim-floaterm)
  13166 </a><a href="#h154-0-73" id="h154-0-73" class="i">+
  13167 </a><a href="#h154-0-74" id="h154-0-74" class="i">+## More plugins
  13168 </a><a href="#h154-0-75" id="h154-0-75" class="i">+
  13169 </a><a href="#h154-0-76" id="h154-0-76" class="i">+Those are my most &quot;showy&quot; plugins. I use a lot more but are just for tiny things like color colorizer, lsp config, color-schemes, etc.
  13170 </a><a href="#h154-0-77" id="h154-0-77" class="i">+I strongly suggest that you vim config should be minimal as you can to get a faster start and use Lua instead of vimrc. This will make your
  13171 </a><a href="#h154-0-78" id="h154-0-78" class="i">+life easier and happier.
  13172 </a><a href="#h154-0-79" id="h154-0-79" class="i">+
  13173 </a><a href="#h154-0-80" id="h154-0-80" class="i">+If you wanna see all my nvim config you can check my repo
  13174 </a><a href="#h154-0-81" id="h154-0-81" class="i">+[nvim configuration](https://github.com/hectoraldairah/nvim-config)
  13175 </a><a href="#h154-0-82" id="h154-0-82" class="i">+
  13176 </a><a href="#h154-0-83" id="h154-0-83" class="i">+It&#39;s not that fancy so maybe you can understand everything there.
  13177 </a><a href="#h154-0-84" id="h154-0-84" class="i">+
  13178 </a><a href="#h154-0-85" id="h154-0-85" class="i">+Well, that it! I know for sure that this plugins list will be changing over time but I will stay with the philosphy of less is more
  13179 </a><b>diff --git a/<a id="h155" href="../file/dist/posts/posts.json.html">dist/posts/posts.json</a> b/<a href="../file/dist/posts/posts.json.html">dist/posts/posts.json</a></b>
  13180 <a href="#h155-0" id="h155-0" class="h">@@ -0,0 +1,4 @@

  13188 </a><a href="#h156-0-1" id="h156-0-1" class="i">+title: &#39;Things I want to learn on 2022&#39;
  13189 </a><a href="#h156-0-2" id="h156-0-2" class="i">+tags: [&#39;Personal&#39;]
  13190 </a><a href="#h156-0-3" id="h156-0-3" class="i">+description: &#39;Some things that catch my attention and I want to learn on 2022.&#39;
  13191 </a><a href="#h156-0-4" id="h156-0-4" class="i">+date: 2021-12-31
  13192 </a><a href="#h156-0-5" id="h156-0-5" class="i">+featured: true
  13193 </a><a href="#h156-0-6" id="h156-0-6" class="i">+---
  13194 </a><a href="#h156-0-7" id="h156-0-7" class="i">+
  13195 </a><a href="#h156-0-8" id="h156-0-8" class="i">+It&#39;s the end of the year, and I&#39;m starting to think about what I want to learn in 2022.
  13196 </a><a href="#h156-0-9" id="h156-0-9" class="i">+
  13197 </a><a href="#h156-0-10" id="h156-0-10" class="i">+1. A new programming language: I&#39;m thinking on Clojure, Elm, or Elixir. I need to understand better the concepts of functional programming and how to use them. Maybe I&#39;ll use this expertise to apply javascript.
  13198 </a><a href="#h156-0-11" id="h156-0-11" class="i">+
  13199 </a><a href="#h156-0-12" id="h156-0-12" class="i">+2. A new pixel art tool: I used to work with Photoshop and Adobe Flash to make pixel art animations, but I don&#39;t want to use them anymore (I can&#39;t run any Adobe App now) so I&#39;m thinking to use [aseprite](https://aseprite.org) because I did some basic animation with it two years ago.
  13200 </a><a href="#h156-0-13" id="h156-0-13" class="i">+
  13201 </a><a href="#h156-0-14" id="h156-0-14" class="i">+3. Blender: I did some 3D animations when I was like 16? on an old mini laptop that I had. It was good at the time with only 2 Gb of ram but man, the software is getting ram expensive. Maybe I can start to make some things with my new computer.
  13202 </a><a href="#h156-0-15" id="h156-0-15" class="i">+4. How to talk in public: Since 2019, I get the interest to do talks about tech with one cup of acid humor on it. The pandemic was a big problem here because there are no more live meetups and I just forget about it. With the online meetups, I can feel a chance to do it.
  13203 </a><a href="#h156-0-16" id="h156-0-16" class="i">+5. Back-end: Well, maybe this is kind of huge for me. I&#39;ve been doing front-end stuff for a while and my backend skills are getting pretty bad. My experience working with [Express](https://expressjs.com/es/) and [Adonis](https://adonisjs.com/) was pretty good, but it was simple things. I don&#39;t know anything about databases too. So, yeah. Maybe I&#39;ll buy a course from [Udemy](https://www.udemy.com/) for it.
  13204 </a><a href="#h156-0-17" id="h156-0-17" class="i">+6. CSS Art: Yes, another art stuff. All the [beautiful CSS art that is on codepen](https://codepen.io/tag/css-art) makes me want to do something similar. I&#39;m not sure what exactly but some 3D CSS animations are on my eye.
  13205 </a><a href="#h156-0-18" id="h156-0-18" class="i">+7. Being fluent in Esperanto and learning more about romantic languages: Duolingo and [Lernu](https://lernu.net/) are my best friends here.
  13206 </a><a href="#h156-0-19" id="h156-0-19" class="i">+
  13207 </a><a href="#h156-0-20" id="h156-0-20" class="i">+That&#39;s it. I don&#39;t want to write more on this post to avoid feeling bad at the end of 2022.
  13208 </a><a href="#h156-0-21" id="h156-0-21" class="i">+
  13209 </a><a href="#h156-0-22" id="h156-0-22" class="i">+Happy 2022!

  13213 </a><a href="#h157-0-1" id="h157-0-1" class="i">+title: &#39;The lie always present in web-dev&#39;
  13214 </a><a href="#h157-0-2" id="h157-0-2" class="i">+tags: [&#39;micro&#39;]
  13215 </a><a href="#h157-0-3" id="h157-0-3" class="i">+description: &quot;I don&#39;t belive you&quot;
  13216 </a><a href="#h157-0-4" id="h157-0-4" class="i">+date: 2023-04-13

  13218 </a><a href="#h157-0-6" id="h157-0-6" class="i">+---
  13219 </a><a href="#h157-0-7" id="h157-0-7" class="i">+
  13220 </a><a href="#h157-0-8" id="h157-0-8" class="i">+Have you ever seen this legend in a lot of websites? It&#39;s ALWAYS in the footer of a web page.
  13221 </a><a href="#h157-0-9" id="h157-0-9" class="i">+
  13222 </a><a href="#h157-0-10" id="h157-0-10" class="i">+&gt; Made with  and (coffee, mushrooms, sugar, etc)
  13223 </a><a href="#h157-0-11" id="h157-0-11" class="i">+
  13224 </a><a href="#h157-0-12" id="h157-0-12" class="i">+Even I use to have it in my old sites.
  13225 </a><a href="#h157-0-13" id="h157-0-13" class="i">+
  13226 </a><a href="#h157-0-14" id="h157-0-14" class="i">+A was thinking about it. It&#39;s kind of weird, isn&#39;t? It&#39;s kinda like a meme of web-development.
  13227 </a><a href="#h157-0-15" id="h157-0-15" class="i">+
  13228 </a><a href="#h157-0-16" id="h157-0-16" class="i">+No one knows where this trend began and I think that is very hard to know it,
  13229 </a><a href="#h157-0-17" id="h157-0-17" class="i">+there is no metrics for this (maybe because it doesn&#39;t matter).
  13230 </a><a href="#h157-0-18" id="h157-0-18" class="i">+
  13231 </a><a href="#h157-0-19" id="h157-0-19" class="i">+I think this is a LIE, yes a very hard lie to tell to our users. Ok, ok, I&#39;m not judging your love and dedication for
  13232 </a><a href="#h157-0-20" id="h157-0-20" class="i">+your site. I think is just a _cliche_ and very burned by now.
